1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 { In part 1 of this database we saw the Rubinstein variation (4.e3) and the Classical variation (4.Qc2) . Here, we will take a look at the other options. } 4. f3 { This is known as the Kmoch variation and is one of the most enterprising lines for White. White wants to immediately get control over the center with the move e4. It is a very commital move weakening the kingside. } ( 4. Qb3 { This has completely gone out of practice and it makes sense as we have a clear way to punish White for bringing his queen out too early. } 4... c5 { This is very effective here with the queen on b3. Ne4 is in the air and the queen is completely misplaced. } ) ( 4. g3 { This position can occur via the Catalan with Bb4+ or the Nimzo. There are many ways for Black to equalise but we need to be well prepared as we are entering Catalan territory which may be new for a few players. } ) ( 4. Bg5 { This is called the Leningrad system and it is one of the more aggressive options for White. However, in modern times it has gone out of practice as engines like the resulting positions for Black. } 4... c5 { We have already seen that this is particularly effective against the Bg5 systems. } ) ( 4. Nf3 { This is called the Kasparov variation and it is one of the most flexible moves as White retains the option to transpose to many different systems. There is always the transposition to the Ragozin with 4...d5 but it is not everyone's cup of tea. } 4... O-O { We do the usual - castle first and decide later. } 5. Bg5 { This is the best independent option for White. 4.e3 will transpose to the lines in my previous course and we will examine 4.Qc2 in the coming chapters. } ( 5. Qc2 { This can occur both via this move order and 4.Qc2. Since we do not go for the lines with d5 there we have to go for an independent option. } 5... c5 { We immediately challenge White's control over the center. } ) 5... c5 { This is something which we have not seen so far in any of the lines but is a very typical plan to break in the center. It is particularly effective against the Bg5 systems as White will face some issues along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 6. Rc1 { This has gotten popular over the last few years. It is a typical modern flexible move keeping options open. While it keeps an eye on c3, White will still likely have to recapture on c3 with the pawn as the rook will get too exposed. } ) ( 4. a3 { This is the Sämisch Variation which is one of the most aggresive and complicated lines against the Nimzo Indian. There are several ways for Black to equalise but the positions are usually quite messy. It has gotten pretty popular in recent times and was also played with success in the World Championship match 2023. } 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 d6 { This is neither one of the common moves in this position nor one of the top choices of the computer. In these lines, the evaluation does not matter as much as a proper understanding of the ideas. Often engines underestimate White's play on the kingside. We play a flexible and cunning move without showing our hand. We keep options of both e5 and c5 open. } ) 4... d5 { This is the more solid alternative, in line with our general plans. We stop White from getting the move e4 easily. However, we will soon diverge from the usual lines. } 5. a3 { This is the only critical way to continue, winning the bishop pair. White will then take on d5 and then slowly prepare the move e4. The knight belongs on g3 in those positions. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c6 { This is our surprise for the opponent. I like such moves which have a conceptual idea in mind. We want to recapture on d5 with the c6 pawn maintaining good control over the center. This takes the sting out of the slow e4 ideas and also opens up the 'c' file. We will take a look at this in the first two chapters. } *

