1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 { This is known as the Kmoch variation and is one of the most enterprising lines for White. White wants to immediately get control over the center with the move e4. It is a very commital move weakening the kingside. } 4... d5 { This is the more solid alternative, in line with our general plans. We stop White from getting the move e4 easily. However, we will soon diverge from the usual lines. } ( 4... c5 { is a very sharp alternative but I am not a fan of the long forcing variations. There are ways in which White can force a draw with good preparation. Having faced such an opponent myself, I wanted to look for other promising options. } ) 5. a3 { This is the only critical way to continue, winning the bishop pair. White will then take on d5 and then slowly prepare the move e4. The knight belongs on g3 in those positions. } ( 5. e3 { Is pretty slow and goes against the spirit of this entire system. } 5... c5 6. a3 Ba5 $1 { We do not need to give up our bishop on c3 immediately. } 7. dxc5 ( 7. cxd5 cxd4 $15 ) 7... Bxc3+ $1 { Now we take on c3 damaging his pawn structure. Releasing the tension with dxc5 was a big concession. } 8. bxc3 Nbd7 $11 { We will take on c5 next with a comfortable position. } ) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c6 $5 { This is our surprise for the opponent. I like such moves which have a conceptual idea in mind. We want to recapture on d5 with the c6 pawn maintaining good control over the center. This takes the sting out of the slow e4 ideas and also opens up the 'c' file. } 7. e3 { This is already a concession as White admits that he is not able to get the move e4 directly. He can try to prepare it slowly but he gives us enough time to create counterplay. } ( 7. a4 { is too slow. } 7... O-O ( 7... Qa5 8. Qd2 O-O 9. e3 { 0-1 (26) Firouzja,A (2728) -Carlsen,M (2863) Lichess.org INT 2020 CBM 198 extra [Krasenkow,Michal] } 9... c5 $11 ) 8. e3 Qc7 { A very flexible move keeping options open. } ( 8... c5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Qd2 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 $11 { [%cal Ge6e5] } ) 9. g4 b6 { We would love to trade off the light-squared bishops. } 10. g5 Ne8 11. Ba3 Nd6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Kf2 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 $11 { Our play on the queenside is much easier and faster. } ) ( 7. Bg5 { This does not make much sense in conjunction with the move f3. } 7... h6 ( 7... O-O { 1-0 (48) Mamedyarov,S (2817) -Karjakin,S (2753) Kolkata 2018 } ) 8. Bh4 ( 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 ) 8... dxc4 9. e4 b5 $11 { It's not going to be easy for White to win back the pawn. } ) ( 7. cxd5 cxd5 $1 { This the reason why we went for the move c6. } 8. Bg5 O-O 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Bd3 e5 $11 { We make use of the 'e' pawn to gain control over the center. We can go for the move e4 next. } ) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 { White is willing to lose a tempo but he wants to get the move e4 on the next move. } ( 8. cxd5 cxd5 { In addition to opening up the 'c' file we also get the c6 square for the knight. b6, Ba6 is the other plan. } 9. Bd3 Nc6 ( 9... b6 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. e4 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 13. O-O $36 ) 10. Ne2 e5 $1 { This perfectly showcases the reason why we went for the move c6. We can fight back in the center with our the 'e' pawn. We will maintain the tension for a long time. } 11. O-O Re8 12. Ng3 h5 $5 { A typical plan aimed against the knight on g3. } 13. h3 ( 13. Ra2 h4 14. Nh1 Be6 $15 ) 13... h4 14. Ne2 b6 $11 ) 8... dxc4 { We have seen this many times in the past- we take on c4 as soon as White moves his light-squared bishop. } ( 8... b6 9. Ne2 ( 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 13. e4 Qc7 ) 9... Ba6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 ( 12... Qc8 13. e4 Qa6 14. Qe3 Nc6 15. e5 Nd7 16. Nf4 Rae8 17. a4 f6 18. exf6 Nxf6 19. Ba3 Rf7 20. Bb4 e5 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (23) Anton Guijarro,D (2642) -Lupulescu,C (2610) Moscow 2019 } ) 13. e4 $36 { [%cal Gc1g5] } 13... Qd7 ( 13... Na5 14. Bg5 ) ( 13... Nd7 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 14. Nf4 Ne7 15. a4 Rc8 ) 14. e5 ( 14. a4 e5 15. Bg5 dxe4 16. fxe4 Ne8 $11 ) 14... Ne8 15. Bg5 f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Rae1 e5 $11 ) 9. Bxc4 c5 { This is similar to one of the variations in the Rubinstein system. There White has his pawn on f2 in the same situation. Pawn on f3 helps prepare e4 but weakens the king. } 10. Ne2 ( 10. e4 Qc7 11. Qc2 cxd4 ( 11... b6 12. Ne2 cxd4 13. cxd4 Ba6 14. Bd3 Qxc2 15. Bxc2 Nc6 16. Ba4 Rac8 17. Be3 Na5 $11 18. Kf2 Rc4 19. Bd1 Rcc8 ) 12. cxd4 Bd7 { We want to go Rc8 next. The bishop is eyeing the a6-f1 diagonal. } 13. Bd3 Qxc2 14. Bxc2 Bb5 { We are going to Nc6 and Rd8 next. It is not easy to defend the d4 pawn. We also do not let him castle easily. } 15. Be3 Nc6 16. Ne2 Rac8 17. Rc1 Rfd8 $11 ) 10... Qc7 11. Bd3 { The general rule in these positions is to go for the e5 plan when the bishop is on d3. This makes sure that White is unable to meet e5 with the move d5. } ( 11. Ba2 b6 $1 { With the bishop on a2 we can get our bishop to the a6-f1 diagonal. } 12. e4 Ba6 13. O-O Nc6 $11 { The d4 pawn is going to come under a lot of pressure. } ) 11... Nc6 12. O-O e5 13. e4 $5 { This is another plan from the previous part- White wants us to get a pawn to d4 to start his play on the center. The pawn keeps the 'd' file closed. } 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 exd4 15. f4 Rd8 16. Ng3 Ng4 $1 { A very important move getting the knight to e3. White can win the pawn back but it opens up some files for our pieces. } 17. Qf3 Ne3 18. Bxe3 dxe3 19. Qxe3 Qb6 $1 { We trade the queens and get the knight to d4. The endgame is roughly equal. } 20. Qxb6 axb6 $11 *

