1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c6 $5 7. e4 { The most critical move and the reason why many Black players avoid this line. We are not going to let White enjoy his centre at all. } 7... dxe4 8. fxe4 e5 $1 { A timely break, opening up the diagonal for the bishop. Our next move is likely to go Bg4 and further weaken the d4 square. } 9. Nf3 Bg4 ( 9... Qa5 10. Bd2 Nxe4 11. Bd3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Be6 ( 12... exd4 13. O-O O-O 14. Ng5 $18 { 1-0 (22) Adhiban,B (2660) -Delgado Ramirez,N (2622) Krasnaya Polyana 2021 CBM 203 [Adhiban,Baskaran] } ) 13. Nxe5 Nd7 14. Nf3 ( 14. Nxd7 Bxd7 ) 14... O-O 15. O-O h6 16. a4 ( 16. Rae1 Rae8 17. h3 Qa6 ) 16... Rae8 17. Rab1 b6 18. Rbe1 Bg4 ) ( 9... Nxe4 10. Qc2 $14 { [%cal Gf1d3,Gf3e5] } ) 10. Qd3 ( 10. Bd3 { White defends the e4 pawn and is ready to castle kingside. We need to go for the critical line here. } 10... exd4 11. e5 Nfd7 12. cxd4 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qh4+ $1 { We trade the queens off by force. The central pawns can be a liability for White. } 14. Qf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 c5 16. Rb1 Nc6 $1 { A pretty unusual idea- we prepare to meet Rb7 with 0-0-0 kicking the rook back. Both the pawns on d4 are e5 are weak. } 17. Rxb7 O-O-O 18. Rb1 cxd4 $11 ) ( 10. h3 { White wants to get his pawn to f3 to bolster his center. This reminds me of the saying- in for a penny in for a pound. His king is anyway open and he would rather make sure that he keeps his center intact. } 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nh5 { It is not clear if we have a killing threat here since the White king can run to the queenside. Our main priority is to keep control over f4 and bring our pieces out quickly. We will likely go Nd7 next. } 12. Rb1 { A cold-blooded move allowing Qh4. But we do not need to go for it. We have a pretty amazing idea prepared. } ( 12. Rg1 Nd7 13. Qd2 h6 14. Rb1 b6 $11 { We want to go Qf6 next. We can also go g5 to keep control over f4. } ) 12... Nd7 ( 12... Qh4+ 13. Kd2 $14 ) 13. Rxb7 Nc5 $3 { I have very rarely seen such an idea work. This is the part which I like about these positions- they are often crazy and imaginative. } 14. Rb2 ( 14. dxc5 $4 Qh4+ 15. Kd2 O-O-O+ $19 ) 14... Qh4+ 15. Kd2 O-O $1 { Another cold-blooded response. Now Black is the one with the initiative. We have a simple plan of getting our pieces to the center and opening up as many files as possible. } 16. Kc2 Rad8 $36 ) 10... exd4 { We want to open the central files and get our king to safety quickly. The position is getting very dynamic with the value of each move sky high. } ( 10... Nbd7 { This was played in a top-level game but I feel our main line is simpler. This can also be analysed in more detail. } 11. dxe5 Nh5 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Qb6+ 14. Rf2 Rfe8 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Rd1 ( 16. c5 $2 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nxe5 18. Qc2 Ng6 19. Kh1 Nhf4 $17 { 1-0 (46) Erigaisi, A (2689) -Parligras, M (2576) Chennai 2022 } ) 16... b6 17. c5 Bxf3 18. Qxd7 Qxd7 19. Rxd7 Bxe2 20. Rxe2 Rxe5 21. cxb6 axb6 22. Bxb6 Nf4 $11 ) 11. cxd4 c5 12. d5 O-O { The first part of our plan is complete. Now the threat is to take on e4. Let us see how long White can hold on to the pawn. } 13. Be2 ( 13. e5 { White decides to give up his 'e' pawn but forces us to bring our rook e5. } 13... Re8 14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Rxe5 16. O-O Nbd7 { We have to study this position carefully. Optically I would assume that White is better but we have enough play to neutralise the bishop pair. We can go for the move b5 next. Another plan is to play along the 'e' file. } 17. Bd3 ( 17. Bb2 Re8 $11 { [%cal Gd8e7,Ge7e3] } ) 17... b5 $1 18. Bf4 ( 18. Bb2 bxc4 19. Bc2 { White is kicking our rook back but at the cost of a pawn. } 19... Re8 { Our plan now is to go Qe3 and play along the 'e' file. } ( 19... Re7 20. d6 Re6 21. Rad1 Qe8 $11 ) 20. Ba4 { White creates some unpleasant pressure on our knights. We need to be very accurate here. } 20... Ne5 $8 21. Qg3 c3 $1 { We give up a pawn to gain a tempo with our knight. The lines are pretty forcing here. } 22. Bxc3 ( 22. Qxc3 Re7 23. Rae1 Nxd5 24. Qg3 Ng6 { Here White has to now play a few only moves. } 25. Bc6 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Rb8 27. Re8+ Qxe8 28. Bxe8 Rxb2 $11 { We will get our knight to f4 next and have at least perpetual check. } ) 22... Ne4 { The queen is tied down to the c3 bishop and we have time to improve our pieces. } 23. Qe3 Ng4 $1 24. Qh3 Re7 25. Bc2 $1 Qxd5 { The lines get messy now but it is objectively equal throughout. } ( 25... Qd6 $5 { is another option. } 26. Bxg7 Nxh2 27. Bxe4 Rxe4 28. Rf6 Qe7 $13 ) 26. Qxg4 Nxc3 27. Bxh7+ Kh8 28. Kh1 Re5 $1 { The rook does a very good job along the 5th rank. } 29. Bf5 Kg8 30. Qh3 g6 31. Bxg6 fxg6 32. Qxc3 Rae8 { The position has simplified and we reach an equal major piece endgame. } ) 18... bxc4 $1 { We want to get our rook to e4. } 19. Bxc4 Re4 20. Rac1 Qb6 21. d6 Rb8 $1 { It is important to maintain control over the 'b' file. We are also preparing to go for the move Ne5 exchanging a pair of minor pieces. The 'd' pawn can be both an asset as well as a liabiltiy. } ( 21... Rae8 22. Rb1 $14 ) 22. Rfe1 ( 22. Kh1 h6 $11 ) 22... Rbe8 $1 { The exchange of rooks works very well for us. } 23. Red1 ( 23. Rxe4 Rxe4 $15 ) 23... h6 $11 { The position is still complicated and all three results are possible. We will put our rook on d4 next. } ) 13... Nbd7 { We bring our knight into the game and stop the move e5. } ( 13... Re8 { is also possible } 14. h3 Bh5 15. e5 Nfd7 16. O-O Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Nd7 19. Bb2 f6 20. Rf5 Nxe5 21. Bxe5 g6 22. Qg4 Qc8 23. Raf1 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (23) Menéndez Rodríguez,G (2357) -Zunkovic,S (2279) ICCF 2019 } ) 14. O-O Qe7 { White has a few options here. We are attacking the e4 pawn and also setting up a blockade on the dark squares. The rook is ready to come to the 'e' file. } 15. Bf4 ( 15. Rb1 b6 16. Nd2 Ne5 17. Qe3 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Ne8 $11 { We have an excellent position with the knight on d6. White cannot do much with his control over the center. } ) ( 15. h3 Bh5 16. Bf4 Rfe8 17. Nd2 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Nxe4 19. Rae1 f5 { We have an extra pawn and it is up to our opponent to prove the compensation. } 20. Nxe4 Qxe4 21. Qxe4 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 fxe4 23. Re1 { Do we have to defend the pawn passively here? } 23... b5 $1 { Of course not, the main point is to get activity for our rook. } 24. cxb5 a6 25. bxa6 Rxa6 $13 ) ( 15. Nd2 Ne5 16. Qe3 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Ne8 $11 ) 15... Rfe8 { We want to get our rook to e4. We will end up winning the e4 pawn soon. } ( 15... Qxe4 $5 16. Qxe4 Nxe4 17. Bd3 Rfe8 18. Rfe1 Nef6 19. Ne5 Nh5 $11 ) 16. Nd2 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Nxe4 18. Rae1 f5 19. Qd3 Ndf6 { All of this happened in the game Abolins-Abols,D (2323) -Ordobs Martínez,V (2314) ICCF 2021. The position is roughly equal but with chances for both sides. } *

