1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 { This is the Sämisch Variation which is one of the most aggresive and complicated lines against the Nimzo Indian. There are several ways for Black to equalise but the positions are usually quite messy. It has gotten pretty popular in recent times and was also played with success in the World Championship match 2023. } 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 d6 { This is neither one of the common moves in this position nor one of the top choices of the computer. In these lines, the evaluation does not matter as much as a proper understanding of the ideas. Often engines underestimate White's play on the kingside. We play a flexible and cunning move without showing our hand. We keep options of both e5 and c5 open. } 6. e3 { This is the 2nd most played move. There are usually 2 approaches for White- to go f3,e4 (we will see this in the next chapter) or to prepare it more slowly with e3, Bd3. Our play is aimed against the latter plan as we want to go e5-e4. } ( 6. Nf3 { This does not fit in with White's previous move and we can take over after } 6... Qe7 $15 { [%cal Ge6e5] } ) ( 6. e4 $5 { This is the best move in the position exploiting the move d6. However, it has hardly been played in any games. The position remains even but we will have to play precisely. } 6... Nxe4 7. Qg4 { This is the point- White wins the g7 pawn in return for his central pawn. } 7... f5 { We are going to force the queens off the board. } ( 7... Nf6 $5 { This can be analysed further but I feel it is not necessary. } 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qh6 Qe7 10. Bd3 ( 10. Nf3 e5 11. Be2 Rg6 12. Qe3 Nc6 13. O-O Ng4 14. Qe4 Bd7 { [%cal Gf7f5,Ge8c8] } ) ( 10. Ne2 Nc6 ( 10... e5 11. f3 $13 ) 11. Ng3 e5 12. d5 Na5 13. Rb1 b6 14. Be2 Rg6 15. Qh4 Nb7 16. O-O Nc5 17. f4 Nxd5 18. Qxh7 Nf6 $11 ) 10... e5 11. Ne2 Rxg2 12. dxe5 Ng4 ( 12... Qxe5 13. Bf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4g3,Ge1c1] } ) 13. exd6 ( 13. Qh3 Rxf2 14. Qxh7 Qxe5 15. Qg8+ Ke7 16. Bg5+ f6 17. Qg7+ Kd8 18. Qg8+ Ke7 19. h3 Rxe2+ 20. Bxe2 Qxc3+ 21. Kf1 Qxa1+ 22. Kg2 Qe5 23. Bxg4 Bxg4 24. hxg4 Kd7 25. Rh7+ Kc6 $11 { [%cal Ge5e2,Ge2e1] } ) ( 13. Qxh7 Nxf2 14. exd6 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 cxd6 $15 ) 13... cxd6 14. Qh3 Rxf2 15. Qxh7 Bf5 16. Qg8+ Qf8 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 18. Bxf5 Rxf5 19. Bf4 Ne5 20. O-O-O Nxc4 21. Rhf1 Ra5 22. Bxd6+ Nxd6 23. Rxd6 Nc6 24. Rd7 Ne5 25. Rxb7 Rxa3 $11 ) 8. Qxg7 Qf6 { We trade queens which makes sense as our king is weaker but at the same time White does have the bishop pair. } 9. Qxf6 ( 9. Qh6 $14 { This is an artificial computer move but we just win the pawn on c3. } 9... Qxh6 10. Bxh6 Nxc3 { It is up to White to show his compensation here. } 11. Ne2 ( 11. Rc1 Na4 12. Be2 Rg8 13. c5 Bd7 $11 { We can get our bishop to the d5 outpost. Again, White has to prove compensation. } ) 11... Na4 { The White knight does not have a great square on the board. } 12. g4 fxg4 13. h3 gxh3 14. Bxh3 Nc6 { We will try to castle queenside next. We are up two pawns and although our opponent has some compensation it should not be for more than equality. } 15. Bg4 Bd7 16. Bh5+ Kd8 17. O-O-O Kc8 18. Bf7 Kb8 19. Nf4 e5 $11 ) 9... Nxf6 10. Bd3 Nc6 { The position is pretty imbalanced. We have two main plans- to go for the e5 break or go b6, Bb7. White also has a few different ways to develop his pieces. The position is completely unexplored though. } 11. Nf3 { The simplest move keeping an eye on the e5 square. However, I hope that its drawbacks are clear. } ( 11. Nh3 Kf7 $11 { [%cal Ge6e5] } ) ( 11. f3 b6 12. Ne2 Kf7 { We prepare to go Ba6 and Na5 next. e5 is another idea to watch out for. } ( 12... Ba6 13. Nf4 Kf7 14. Nxe6 $14 ) 13. g4 Ba6 14. gxf5 e5 $1 { The pawn on f5 keeps our king safe and the d3 bishop restricted. Na5 is hard to stop now. } 15. Kf2 ( 15. Bg5 Rae8 { We want to go e4 next. } 16. O-O-O e4 17. fxe4 Nxe4 18. Bh4 Na5 $36 { [%csl Rc4] 1-0 (27) Asi,E (1608) -Klemmer,M (2020) ICCF email 2021 } ) 15... Na5 16. Bh6 Bxc4 17. Be4 Rae8 { We have the better pawn structure which is compensated by the bishop pair. The position is dynamically balanced. } ) 11... e5 { We get to go e5 with a tempo threatening to go e4 next. } 12. Nh4 { White is provoking us to go for the move e4 which would weaken the dark squares. The d4 pawn is hanging but that is exactly what our opponent wants to achieve- to open up the center. } ( 12. Bc2 Rg8 13. O-O Bd7 { We will go 0-0-0 next and it is not easy for White to get rid of our control over the center. } 14. c5 e4 15. Nh4 dxc5 16. dxc5 Be6 $11 { We can castle long next with a great position. } ) 12... Bd7 { A clever move as White was not yet threatening to take on f5. } ( 12... e4 13. Be2 $14 ) 13. O-O ( 13. Bxf5 exd4 14. cxd4 Nxd4 $36 { [%cal Gd4b3,Gb3c1,Gb3a1] } ) 13... f4 { Since we have the light-squared bishop we should be placing our pawns on the dark squares, restricting his dark-squared bishop. } 14. c5 O-O-O 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Re1 Rhg8 $11 { The position remains pretty complex but it is dynamically balanced. } ) 6... O-O 7. Bd3 { This is the most common plan after 4.a3 but we are specifically playing against this system with our move order. } ( 7. Nf3 { This goes completely against the spirit of the move 4.a3. White cannot afford to play slowly as he is positionally worse due to his pawn structure. } 7... Qe7 8. Be2 c5 $15 { We will go e5 next and the closed center suits our pieces much better. } ) ( 7. Ne2 { White tries to get his knight to g3 before developing the bishop. It takes up quite a bit of time though. It was famously played by Ding against Nepo in the World Championship match 2023 and we must take it very seriously. } 7... c5 8. Ng3 ( 8. d5 e5 $17 ) 8... Nc6 { We want to go b6, Ba6 next followed by Na5. It is one of the main plans against an early a3. } 9. Ra2 $5 { This was the move popularised by Ding Liren but I am sure it was analysed by a lot of players before that. In one of the training camps for the Chennai Olympiad 2022, I analysed this position briefly for the Indian team with Adhiban. It usually leads to very interesting positions provided that the Black player is not aware of the details. } ( 9. e4 { This is very risky with the king on e1. } 9... d5 $1 { Now, we are happy to open up the central files. } 10. e5 Ne4 11. Qc2 { This is the only way to keep complex. The following line leads to an endgame practically by force. } 11... cxd4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Qa5 14. Bd3 Qxe5 15. cxd4 Qxe4+ 16. Bxe4 Nxd4 $36 { We are a pawn up in the endgame. White may be able to win back the pawn but we also have the better structure. } ) ( 9. Bd3 { This is the standard plan here. White will try to create play on the kingside as quickly as possible. } 9... b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. Qe2 ( 11. f4 { can be met with } 11... d5 $1 12. cxd5 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 exd5 14. dxc5 { White wants to go c4 next and open up the diagonal for his bishop. } 14... Na5 $1 { We keep control over the c4 square sacrificing a pawn in the process. } 15. cxb6 Qxb6 $44 { The bishop on c1 is completely restricted by his pawns. } ) 11... Rc8 { Let's bring more pieces to go after the c4 pawn. } 12. Bb2 ( 12. d5 $2 Ne5 $19 ) ( 12. Bd2 $5 { I think that this is the best for White keeping the bishop along this diagonal. } 12... Na5 13. d5 $14 Nd7 14. f4 $1 { White stops our knight from getting to the ideal e5 square. } 14... exd5 15. cxd5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 c4 17. Qc2 Nb3 18. Rae1 Ndc5 $11 { We get the other knight to d3. The position remains complex but I would rather be Black here with the dancing knights. } ) 12... Na5 13. Rac1 ( 13. d5 { Leads to a slightly worse position after } 13... Nd7 $15 { [%cal Gd7e5] } ) 13... Qd7 { No mercy for him! The queen is heading to a4 now and White has to go for broke here. He cannot defend the c4 pawn anymore. } 14. e4 Qa4 15. e5 dxe5 16. dxe5 Ne8 { Even though we have 3 pieces on the 'a' file, White is unable to create anything in time on the kingside. } 17. Rcd1 Bxc4 18. Bc1 { Finally the bishop comes into the game but it is quite late to the party. } 18... Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Nc6 $36 { We will go c4 next and exchange rooks along the 'd' file. White has to work to show compensation. } ) 9... Qa5 $14 { I like to deviate early from the well-trodden path. We want to discoordinate White's pieces and tie them down to the c3 pawn. } ( 9... b6 { This was the main line of my analysis and what Nepo played. You can check this more deeply on your own. } 10. e4 Ba6 11. Bg5 h6 12. h4 $1 { White keeps the tension on the kingside. } 12... hxg5 { The most direct way. } 13. hxg5 g6 14. gxf6 Qxf6 15. e5 ( 15. Qg4 { This is what I had prepared for White before that game. } 15... cxd4 16. Nh5 Qe5 17. f4 Qxe4+ 18. Be2 Qb1+ 19. Bd1 Qe4+ $11 ) 15... dxe5 16. d5 $5 { This is where Ding deviates from the top line of the computer. } 16... Ne7 17. d6 Nf5 18. Ne4 Qd8 19. Qd3 Kg7 20. g4 Bb7 21. Rh3 Nh4 22. g5 { All this happened in 1/2-1/2 (45) Ding, L (2788) -Nepomniachtchi, I (2795) Astana 2023. Black would have been fine after } 22... Rh8 $1 23. f4 exf4 24. Nf6 e5 25. Rah2 Nf3+ 26. Qxf3 Bxf3 27. Rh7+ Rxh7 28. Rxh7+ Kf8 29. Rh8+ Kg7 $11 ) 10. Rd2 ( 10. Bd2 { This beats the purpose of going Ra2 and we can just go back. } 10... Qc7 $11 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] } ) 10... d5 { With a lead in development we are happy to open up the center. } 11. cxd5 ( 11. Bb2 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 { We can go for the move e5 next. The bishop on b2 is completely shut down. } 13. Qc2 f5 $11 ) 11... exd5 { We want to go c4 now and keep the center closed. We are playing against the bishop on c1. } 12. Be2 c4 13. Qc2 Re8 14. O-O Bd7 $11 { We can go Ne7 followed by Ba4. On the kingside we can try to go h5-h4. The position is balanced. } ) 7... e5 $1 { This is the reason why we went for the move d6 instead of the usual c5 plan. We will go e4 followed by Be6 playing against the c4 pawn. Nc6-a5 is another idea. } 8. Ne2 { The natural continuation but it allows us to execute our master plan. } ( 8. f3 { He tries to stop the move e4 but this is just asking for it. } 8... e4 $1 9. fxe4 Nxe4 10. Nf3 Bf5 $15 { We have full control over e4. } ) ( 8. e4 { White stops us from going e4 but do not forget that his king is still on e1. How do we exploit that? } 8... exd4 9. cxd4 Nxe4 $1 { We win the central pawn opening up the 'e' file. White has to treat this as a sacrifice and make use of his bishop pair. The position is still dynamically balanced. } 10. Ne2 ( 10. Bxe4 Re8 $17 ) 10... d5 { We will try to keep our knight in the center until he makes some concession to force us back. } 11. O-O Re8 12. Ng3 ( 12. Qc2 Bf5 13. cxd5 Qxd5 14. Nf4 Qc6 $11 ) 12... Nd7 { We want to bolster our knight on e4. } 13. Qc2 Ndf6 14. c5 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Bd7 $11 { White has some compensation with the bishop pair but not more. } ) 8... e4 $1 { We close down the center and restrict his dark-squared bishop. } 9. Bb1 Be6 $1 { It would be great to force the move d5 as it gives up the e5 square. Otherwise, it is not easy to defend c4. } 10. Ba2 { This has been played very few times but is a natural continuation. } ( 10. Qb3 Nbd7 { We want to get our knight to b6 to attack the c4 pawn. } 11. Ng3 ( 11. Nf4 { Distracts our bishop but the knight is misplaced on f4. } 11... Bf5 12. O-O Rb8 $15 { [%csl Rb1,Rc1][%cal Gc7c6] } ) 11... Nb6 ( 11... b5 $5 ) 12. d5 Bg4 { This is a surprising inclusion as it turns out that the inclusion of move h3 might be beneficial for us. It is pretty deep but also not strictly necessary. } ( 12... Bc8 { [%cal Gb6d7,Gd7c5] is very similar. } ) 13. h3 Bc8 { We would love to get our knight to c5. White's pawns on the queenside are a long-term problem for him. } 14. Nxe4 { We do give up the central pawn but we will make sure that White is not able to open up the center. } 14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 f5 16. Bc2 Nd7 $11 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gb7b6] The knight will be perfect on c5. } ) ( 10. Ng3 { This is a good trade for us as we stop White from castling kingside. He will likely have to trade the light-squared bishops and be stuck with the amazing bishop on c1. } 10... Bxc4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Nc6 { This has been played in only one game so far by Gukesh. We want to get out knight to c4 quickly. } ( 12... d5 { is a simpler option. } 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Nd7 15. c4 Nb6 $1 16. cxd5 Qxd5 $11 { We will go c5 next. } ) 13. Bd3 ( 13. Bb1 f5 $17 { [%csl Re1][%cal Gf5f4] } ) ( 13. Rb1 Rb8 14. Bd3 Na5 $11 ) 13... Na5 $1 { This was the reason to go for the move Nc6. The c4 square will be an outpost for our knight. } 14. Rb1 ( 14. O-O d5 $15 { [%csl Rc1] } ) 14... Bxd3 { I think this is slightly better as we do not let White go e4 and open up the center. } ( 14... d5 { was played in the game 0-1 (58) Gupta, A (2628) -Gukesh, D (2614) New Delhi 2022 } 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 $15 16. e4 $1 b6 17. Qd3 ) 15. Qxd3 d5 16. O-O f5 $17 { This is the point- we get full control over the center and restrict the bishop. The knight will eventually get to c4. } ) 10... Nc6 $5 { We are preparing to go Na5 next. White has to act quickly. } ( 10... Nbd7 { This is a simpler and maybe even better option objectively. It does not lead to forcing play here. } 11. Nf4 Bf5 12. h3 c6 $11 { We can go h6 next and we have a pleasant middlegame. I like our chances more. } ) 11. d5 $1 { White has to enter these complications. } ( 11. O-O { is too slow and allows us to execute our plan. } 11... Na5 12. d5 Bd7 13. Ng3 b6 $17 { [%csl Rc3,Rc4] } ) 11... Ne5 12. dxe6 Nd3+ 13. Kf1 Ng4 { This must look very scary to play for White and he has to find some only moves. } 14. Nf4 Ngxf2 15. e7 $1 { This is very important here not allowing us to open the 'f' file. } 15... Qxe7 16. Qd2 { Again the only move. This is a weird square for the queen but necessary as exd3 should not come with a tempo. } ( 16. Qe2 $4 Nxh1 17. Nxd3 exd3 18. Qxd3 Qf6+ $19 ) 16... Nxh1 17. Nxd3 exd3 18. Kg1 { We have quite a few options here to continue our initiative. } 18... Qf6 ( 18... Rae8 { is a promising option. } 19. Kxh1 f5 20. Qxd3 f4 21. c5+ d5 22. Bxd5+ Kh8 23. e4 c6 24. Bb3 Qxe4 25. Qxe4 Rxe4 26. Kg1 $11 ) 19. Bb2 Rae8 20. Kxh1 Re4 { This is a very messy position but dynamically balanced. We will look to create something quickly on the kingside. } 21. Kg1 Qe5 22. Re1 Re8 23. Bc1 Rh4 24. g3 Re6 $1 { We bring all our pieces into the game. There are too many options here to analyse very deeply. I think this is already far from the realms of possibility in a practical game. } 25. Qxd3 Rh3 26. Re2 Rg6 27. Rg2 ( 27. Qd2 Rgxg3+ 28. hxg3 Qxg3+ 29. Rg2 Qh4 30. Kf1 Rh1+ 31. Rg1 Rh2 32. Rg2 $11 ) 27... Rxh2 28. Kxh2 Qh5+ 29. Kg1 Rh6 30. Kf2 Rf6+ $11 *

