1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 d6 ( 5... c5 6. f3 d6 { transposes. } ) 6. f3 { This is the most played move in this position. However, the f3 plan in general is less popular compared to the safer e3, Bd3 plan. White is going all in to get control over the center. We will fight back on the queenside playing against the c4 pawn. I prefer to keep the king in the center for the time being. } 6... c5 { We transpose back into the main lines having avoided the critical e3 lines. } 7. e4 Nc6 { We make sure that White is not able to go Bd3, Ne2 easily as the d4 pawn is weak. We have two broad plans- to go e5 and close the center or to go b6, Na5, Ba6 and fight for the c4 pawn. In most cases, we will go after the c4 pawn maintaining the tension. } 8. Be3 { White wants to get his bishop to d3 and he first needs to defend his pawn on d4. } ( 8. Nh3 $6 { This plan is too slow here and we can exploit it immediately with } 8... e5 9. d5 Bxh3 $1 10. dxc6 Bc8 11. cxb7 Bxb7 $17 { We have managed to exchange the important d5 pawn for b7. Black was better in the game 0-1 (47) Bhakti, K (2281) -Ghosh, D (2570) Mumbai 2016. } ) ( 8. d5 { is premature releasing the tension in the center. } 8... Na5 9. Bd3 b6 { We will go hard after the c4 pawn. I like the plan of castling queenside as White has already closed the center. } 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O Qe7 $1 { The king will be very safe on c8. It is hard to see where White is going to play next. } ( 11... O-O 12. Bg5 $14 ) ( 11... Nd7 12. f4 $13 ) 12. Ng3 ( 12. f4 O-O-O $15 ) 12... O-O-O { We can go Nd7 next and bring the knight to e5. Another plan is to go h5-h4 and play on the kingside. } ) ( 8. Ne2 { The knight is heading to g3 before the development of the f1 bishop. } 8... b6 9. Ng3 ( 9. Bg5 { White creates a potential threat of going for the move e5. } 9... h6 10. Bh4 O-O $1 { This is a rare case of us castling kingside very early. The justification is that it is extremely difficult for White to create anything on the kingside with his lack of development. The knight cannot go to g3 or f4 as it will run into g5. } ( 10... Bb7 11. Nc1 cxd4 12. cxd4 e5 13. Nb3 $16 { 1-0 (52) Salem,A (2679) -Moussard,J (2631) Sharjah 2021 } ) 11. Nc1 { This looks like a terrible square for the knight but he wants to go to b3 from where it stops Na5 and also defends the c4 pawn. } ( 11. f4 e5 $1 { We would love to open up the center. } 12. d5 Na5 13. f5 g5 $19 ) 11... Ba6 12. Nb3 { White is just in time but we now switch plans. } 12... Ne7 $1 { The knight is heading to g6 and we are willing to weaken our pawn structure on the kingside. } 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Be2 f5 { This is the benefit of doubling our pawns. We plan to go f4 and Ng6 followed by play on the kingside. } 15. Qd2 Kg7 16. O-O Ng6 $11 ) 9... O-O { Once again we castle very early. White has wasted a couple of tempi with Ne2-g3 and his setup is not that aggressive. Moreover, as I already mentioned, he cannot combine Ne2-g3 with Bg5 easily. } ( 9... Qc7 $6 { Happened in the game 1-0 (43) Salem, A (2690) -Moussard, J (2630) Abu Dhabi 2021 but White gets an edge after } 10. Bg5 $14 ) 10. Be2 { This is not the most active square for the bishop but it is the quickest way to complete development. } ( 10. h4 { White prepares to go Bg5 next and he will want to keep the bishop there even after h6. } 10... h6 { We stop it as he cannot sacrifice the piece immediately. White needed to follow up with f4 to keep the bishop there. } ( 10... Ba6 11. Bg5 h6 12. f4 $13 ) 11. Bf4 ( 11. Bg5 $2 cxd4 12. cxd4 hxg5 13. hxg5 Nh7 14. f4 g6 $19 ) 11... e5 12. Be3 { White provoked the move e5 to get the f5 square for the knight. We want to open up the position now. } 12... exd4 13. cxd4 cxd4 14. Bxd4 Be6 $11 ) 10... Ba6 11. O-O Na5 12. f4 $1 { Now it becomes a race- we are trying to be greedy and win a pawn on the queenside while White is trying to create an initiative on the kingside. } 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bxc4 14. f5 h6 { An important prophylactic move stopping Bg5. It is not easy for White to do much on the kingside. } 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Rb1 e5 17. d5 Rc8 18. Nh5 Na5 { We want to get our rook to c4 putting pressure on the e4 pawn. } 19. Qf3 ( 19. Rb4 { This is too desperate trying to stop Rc4. } 19... Rc3 20. Bd2 { Happened in the game 0-1 (33) Giri, A (2764) -Praggnanandhaa, R (2678) chess24.com INT 2022. Black was almost winning after } 20... Rxa3 21. Qc1 Rd3 22. Nxg7 Kxg7 23. Bxh6+ Kh7 $19 ) 19... Rc4 20. Rb4 Rc2 21. Rb1 $11 { White had to repeat to maintain the balance while we have a few options to keep the game going. } ) 8... b6 { We will go after the pawn on c4. I like to keep my king in the center keeping both options open. We will usually go Ba6, Na5 and Qc7 first. } 9. Bd3 Na5 ( 9... e5 { Was played in the game 0-1 (46) Vitiugov,N (2727) -Oparin,G (2654) Riga 2021. It does not fit in with White's development. } 10. Ne2 $14 ) 10. Ne2 ( 10. Nh3 { White wants to castle and go for the move f4. The knight does not block the queen's path. } 10... e5 $5 { We immediately stop the plan of f4. The knight is not well placed to take advantage of our play. } 11. Nf2 Ba6 12. O-O Nd7 $1 { A nice multipurpose move- we stop Bg5 and also create a threat of taking on c4. } ( 12... O-O 13. Bg5 { [%cal Rg5d8] } ) 13. Qa4 ( 13. Re1 O-O $15 { [%csl Rc4,Rf2] } ) ( 13. f4 Bxc4 { White does not have much compensation for the pawn in practical play. I will challenge you to find the top choice of the computer here :) } ) 13... cxd4 { This is the simplest as we open the 'c' file for our rook and also prepare to bring the knight to c5. } ( 13... Rc8 $5 14. d5 Qe7 { I like the plan of Kd8-c7 here. This is a typical plan for these positions as the queenside is completely closed. } ) 14. cxd4 O-O 15. Rac1 exd4 16. Bxd4 Nc5 17. Bxc5 dxc5 { We have the better bishop and pawn structure. } ) 10... Ba6 11. O-O ( 11. Ng3 Qc7 { will likely transpose. } ) 11... Qc7 $1 { As I mentioned earlier we keep both options open for as long as possible. The other point is to stop his idea of Bg5 especially when we castle kingside. } 12. Ng3 ( 12. f4 O-O-O $1 { the point of blacks play...he is very flexible with the king } 13. f5 e5 14. d5 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Bg5 Nxe4 17. Bxd8 Rxd8 $15 ) 12... O-O { [%csl Rc4] We have already seen that with the knight on g3, we can commit to castling kingside. } 13. f4 { This is in the spirit of the position- to go for an all-out attack against our king. } ( 13. Rf2 { White is trying to preserve the bishops on the board but it wastes a lot of time. } 13... Bxc4 14. Bc2 Rac8 $15 ) 13... Bxc4 14. f5 cxd4 15. cxd4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qc4 { We are going to try our best to get the queens off the board. } 17. Qd1 h6 { We first stop ideas of Bg5. Let us see what White is going to try on the kingside. } ( 17... Qb3 18. Qe1 { [%cal Ge3g5] } ) 18. Kh1 ( 18. Rc1 Qb3 $11 ) 18... Rac8 ( 18... Qb3 19. Qe2 e5 $11 ) 19. Nh5 Nxh5 20. Qxh5 exf5 21. exf5 Rfe8 22. Bxh6 { This is the only way to keep the balance for White. } 22... Qxd4 23. Rad1 Qe5 24. Rf3 Qe1+ 25. Rf1 Qe5 { A very professional repetition of moves :) } *

