1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 { This is called the Kasparov variation and it is one of the most flexible moves as White retains the option to transpose to many different systems. There is always the transposition to the Ragozin with 4...d5 but it is not everyone's cup of tea. } 4... O-O { We do the usual - castle first and decide later. } 5. Bg5 { This is the best independent option for White. 4.e3 will transpose to the lines in my previous course and we will examine 4.Qc2 in the coming chapters. } 5... c5 { This is something which we have not seen so far in any of the lines but is a very typical plan to break in the center. It is particularly effective against the Bg5 systems as White will face some issues along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 6. e3 { This is the positional way, maintaining the tension but it is slow. } ( 6. a3 { I do not see the point of this move at all and it helps us take over the initiative quickly. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5 8. Qc2 Ne4 9. Bd2 { A pretty sad move to play. } 9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 d6 $11 { We will go e5 next with a great position due to our better pawn structure and the better minor piece. } ) ( 6. Qb3 { White brings his queen out early but there is no real threat and we will keep maintaining the tension. } 6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6 { We are provoking White into doing something in the center. } 8. d5 { This has been played by Yu Yangyi in the past but it is a risky pawn sacrifice. } ( 8. dxc5 $6 { This has been played a few times but it is an inaccuracy as it weakens White's pawn structure. } 8... g5 $1 { This is something we should come to expect in the Nimzo. It is one of the few openings where I see Black taking over the initiative very early in the game. } 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. e3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc5 $15 { The queenside structure is a sorry sight for White. } ) ( 8. e3 { This is a solid approach, maintaining tension. } 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. exd4 Be7 { We retreat calmly and prepare b6, Bb7. We will go d5 at the right moment and try to force White into an IQP position. } 11. Be2 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 d5 $11 ) 8... Na5 9. Qc2 Nxc4 10. O-O-O b5 $1 { I do not think there is any reason to trade on c3 next and we are looking to open up the lines on the queenside. } ( 10... Bxc3 { happened in the aforementioned game } 11. Qxc3 b5 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. e4 Bb7 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. dxe6 dxe6 17. Rhe1 Rfd8 18. Re3 Rd3 19. Rdxd3 cxd3 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (31) Yu,Y (2763) -Ding,L (2811) Khanty Mansiysk 2019 } ) 11. Nxb5 Nxb2 $1 { The most enterprising option. There is an important concept in attack called the elimination of the 'b/g' pawn. This is usually the key to getting to the opponent's king as it exposes a lot of squares. } ( 11... a6 { is also good } ) 12. Qxb2 Rb8 { The following sequence is practically forced. } 13. a3 Rxb5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. axb4 Rxb4 16. Qa1 { A pretty nice square for the queen :) There is an alarming lack of pawns in White's queenside. } 16... exd5 17. e3 d4 18. exd4 c4 $1 19. d5 Qb6 $40 { White has to continue playing only moves to survive here. } ) ( 6. d5 { White is overextending his center with the king still stuck in the center for a while. We get a fantastic version of the Benoni. } 6... exd5 7. cxd5 d6 8. e3 Nbd7 { I want to immediately go Nb6 and try to win the pawn on d5. We can always go h6, g5 and kick the bishop back. } 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bh4 Nb6 11. e4 ( 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nbxd5 $11 { I doubt if White has enough compensation for the pawn even though the evaluation is close to zeros according to comp. } ) 11... g5 $1 { We have to play dynamically before White manages to get his king to safety. } 12. Bg3 ( 12. Nxg5 { This shoul always be checked properly. } 12... hxg5 13. Bxg5 Qe7 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 14. f4 Nbxd5 $1 15. O-O Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bxc3 { There are a lot of options here for both sides. I will give you a sample line. } 17. Kh1 Re8 18. Rc1 Bd4 19. e5 dxe5 20. fxe5 Bxe5 21. Qd2 { [%cal Gg5f6,Gd2h6] } 21... Bg4 22. h3 Rad8 23. Rce1 Rd6 24. Bh4 Bh5 { [%cal Gh5g6] } 25. Qh6 Bg6 26. Bxg6 fxg6 27. Rxe5 Qxe5 28. Qxg6+ $11 ) 12... Re8 { [%csl Re4] White is forced to give up his pawn here but he retains some compensation due to our exposed king. } 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Rxe4 16. Nd2 Re8 17. Qh5 Qf6 { Once we get our bishop to f5 we are just better. } 18. f4 g4 19. f5 Qg5 $11 { We are up a pawn in the endgame although the game will probably simplify soon. } ) 6... cxd4 { We practically force White into an IQP position if he wants to play for something here. } 7. exd4 ( 7. Nxd4 Qa5 $1 { We win a pawn by force here. } 8. Bxf6 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Ke2 gxf6 $11 { The engine claims that White has some compensation with precise play but it is very easy to go wrong. } ) ( 7. Qxd4 { allows us to gain a tempo with } 7... Nc6 8. Qf4 h6 9. h4 { The principled way trying to create something on the kingside. As we know, a flank attack should be countered in the center. } ( 9. Bxf6 { leads to a nice endgame with the bishop pair. } 9... Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Rc1 b6 $11 ) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Re8 { We want to go e5 kicking the queen to a bad square. } 11. O-O-O e5 12. Bxf6 exf4 13. Bxd8 fxe3 $1 { A nice intermediate move. } 14. Bc7 e2 $11 { This was the point of the rook on e8. We now reach a good endgame with a better pawn structure. } ) 7... d5 { This is a great version of the traditional lines in the Karpov variation. We have a lead in development and are the ones having the choice to release the tension in the center. } 8. Rc1 { White plays a useful waiting move maintaining tension. } ( 8. cxd5 { White wants to develop his bishop without allowing dxc4 but it opens up the diagonal for our light-squared bishop. } 8... exd5 9. Be2 h6 10. Bh4 ( 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. O-O Be6 $11 { We will go Nc6 next with a comfortable position. } ) 10... g5 { Time to play for the initiative. We go for it just before he can castle. } 11. Bg3 Ne4 12. Rc1 Nc6 13. O-O Bf5 $13 { [%cal Ge4c3,Gb4a3,Gh6h5] We have a more active position and good chances to take over in the middlegame. } ) ( 8. Be2 { Both the bishop moves waste a tempo as they will have to recapture on c4. We have a tempo up on the Karpov variation which is already completely fine for Black. } 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 ( 9. O-O a6 { We want to meet Bxc4 with b5 and Bb7. } 10. a4 { Thanks for the weakness on b4! } 10... Nc6 11. Bxc4 h6 12. Bh4 Be7 $11 { We can continue normally with Bd7 and Rc8. b4 is a big weakness for White. } ) 9... a6 { Usually, we are not able to play this slowly but with an extra tempo we can afford the luxury. } 10. O-O ( 10. a4 { creates a big weakness as usual. } 10... h6 11. Bh4 Qc7 12. Qd3 Nd5 $11 { [%cal Gd5f4] } ) 10... b5 11. Bd3 Bb7 { We have an excellent version of the IQP structure with very good control over d5. The exchange of minor pieces is usually in our favour here. } 12. a4 ( 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. Qe2 h6 14. Bh4 Rc8 15. Ne5 Re8 $11 { We can allow White to double our pawns on the kingside. We have a very comfortable position. } ) 12... h6 13. Bh4 ( 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Bxa8 16. Nxb5 Rd8 $11 { We will win back the pawn very soon with an equal endgame. } ) 13... bxa4 14. Ne5 Be7 $11 15. Rxa4 Nbd7 $11 { I feel White is the one who has to be careful here not to get positionally outplayed in the resulting endgames. } ) 8... h6 { I always like to force the bishop back when given the chance. You never know when we can go g5 and Ne4 in these positions. } ( 8... Be7 9. a3 ( 9. Be2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 h6 11. Bf4 Nc6 12. O-O b6 $11 ) ( 9. Bd3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 h6 11. Bf4 ( 11. Bh4 ) ) 9... b6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Bb5 a6 13. Ba4 b5 14. Bb3 Re8+ $15 { 1/2-1/2 (35) Carlsen, M (2855) -Nakamura, H (2787) Paris 2016 } ) 9. Bh4 Nc6 { Our threat now is to go e5 and completely blast open the center. White has to be very careful. } 10. a3 ( 10. c5 $2 { is just asking for it. } 10... e5 $1 11. dxe5 d4 12. exf6 g5 $17 { We will go Re8 next and Be2 will be met with d3. White is in deep trouble. } ) ( 10. Bd3 { We have seen a similar position on the previous move. } 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 Be7 12. O-O Nh5 $5 { We trade the dark-squared bishops and also bring the knight in contact with the d5 square. } 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Ne5 Nf6 $11 { We can continue with Bd7 and Rc8 next. } ) 10... Be7 $1 { This is something which we have to keep in mind. It is very tempting to trade on c3 but instead, we are looking to go for Ne4 next. } ( 10... Bxc3+ 11. Rxc3 $14 { White has the edge here even with the king in the center. Our bishop is pretty passive on c8. } 11... g5 12. Nxg5 $18 ) 11. c5 { This is necessary to develop the bishop on f1. } 11... Ne4 $1 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 { Now White has to be very careful as we might break with e5 at any moment. } 13. Be2 ( 13. Bb5 { Happened in a high-level game but we have a straightforward continuation to fight for the initiative. } 13... Nxc3 14. Rxc3 e5 $1 15. O-O ( 15. dxe5 d4 16. Rc1 Nxe5 $11 ) 15... e4 { This is the most ambitious move keeping a pair of pieces on the board. } ( 15... Bg4 $11 { Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (58) Carlsen, M (2855) -Nakamura,H (2787) Leuven 2016. The position simplified soon to a draw. } ) 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Ne5 Qe8 $11 { f6 is a big threat and the position remains dynamically balanced. } ) 13... Rd8 $1 { An important move to prepare e5 and open up the diagonal for the bishop. } ( 13... Nxc3 { is too early. } 14. Rxc3 e5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Re3 $1 ) 14. O-O e5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 d4 { The position has simplified and we reach an equal middlegame/endgame. I think there are likely to be a few simplifications which result in a drawn rook endgame. } 18. Rc1 Qxe5 19. Bd3 ( 19. Bf3 d3 $1 20. Qd2 Rb8 { The bishop will come to f5 next and the pawn becomes a big asset for us. } ) 19... Bf5 { This happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (47) Wojtaszek,R (2733) -Kramnik,V (2792) Dortmund 2018 and I think it is a good place for us to stop. The endgame is pretty even. } *

