1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Bg5 c5 6. Rc1 { This has gotten popular over the last few years. It is a typical modern flexible move keeping options open. While it keeps an eye on c3, White will still likely have to recapture on c3 with the pawn as the rook will get too exposed. } 6... h6 { It is always useful to kick the bishop back as we can break the pin in one go with g5. We usually go for it when we are sure that the capture on f6 is not great. } 7. Bh4 ( 7. Bxf6 { It is rarely a good idea to give up the bishop so early in the game. White will probably win our dark-squared bishop but we are ahead in development. } 7... Qxf6 8. e3 b6 9. Be2 Nc6 { We are looking to trade on d4 and play against White's shaky center. } 10. O-O cxd4 11. exd4 Bb7 $11 { We will go d5 at the right moment and I believe that the d4 pawn is a liability for White. } ) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 d5 $1 { We will play dynamically here making use of our lead in development. Our only issue is to get the light-squared bishop out into the game. } 9. cxd5 ( 9. Bxf6 { The Only reason is to force an IQP but we do have a huge development advantage. } 9... Qxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. e3 Nc6 12. Be2 Nxd4 $11 { We are at least fine with the bishop pair. } ) ( 9. e3 { Is too slow and runs into } 9... e5 $1 10. Nf3 ( 10. Nb3 g5 { A common occurrence in this line, getting out of the nasty pin. } ( 10... d4 { is also possible } 11. exd4 exd4 12. Qxd4 g5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bg3 Ne4 15. f3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 $11 ) 11. Bg3 Nc6 { We are threatening to go d4 next which is very powerful with the king on e1. } 12. a3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 dxc4 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bxc4 Ne4 { Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (46) Li, C (2746) -Giri, A (2755) Moscow 2016. We have a very pleasant endgame with the better pawn structure. } ) 10... d4 $1 { We are happy to open up the center. } 11. exd4 exd4 12. Qxd4 ( 12. Nxd4 Qb6 $1 { [%cal Gf8d8] The position is very risky for White. } 13. a3 { The only move which keeps the balance. } ( 13. Nf3 Rd8 14. Qc2 g5 15. Bg3 Nc6 $17 { [%cal Gg5g4,Gc6d4] 0-1 (35) Edouard,R (2613) -Nakamura,H (2785) Caleta 2017 CBM 177 [Navara,D] } ) 13... Rd8 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. axb4 Rxd4 16. Qe2 Be6 $36 { The position remains unpleasant for White and we will win the pawn on c$ soon> } ) 12... g5 13. Bg3 ( 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bg3 Ne4 15. Be2 Re8 $11 { [%cal Re8e1] } ) 13... Nc6 { We are happy to go into the endgame with our active pieces despite being a pawn down. } 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Be2 Ne4 16. O-O Bxc3 17. bxc3 Be6 $44 { We have full compensation for the pawn and are likely to win the pawn on c4 shortly. } ) 9... g5 $1 { We want to take on d5 with the queen. The game is getting very concrete and White's king is likely to be in the center for the time being. } 10. Bg3 Qxd5 { We are sneakily threatening to take on a2. Another plan is to go e5 and bring our light-squared bishop out. } 11. e3 ( 11. h4 { This has been played in only one game between Inarkiev, E (2682) -Karjakin, S Nazran 2019. There are multiple ways to equalise and I will try to go for the easiest one. } 11... Ne4 12. e3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Nxg3 14. fxg3 Nd7 { We have damaged White's pawn structure and will bring our knight to e4. White has to shift to damage control mode and trade queens. } 15. Qf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 g4 17. fxg4 Ne5 $11 { [%csl Ge5] The knight has a beautiful outpost on e5 and we have more than enough compensation with White's weak pawns. } ) ( 11. a3 { White decides to force us to trade the bishops on c3. } 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 ( 12. Rxc3 $6 e5 $15 { [%cal Gd5d1,Gf6e4] } ) 12... Ne4 { e5 is a big threat now and I feel we are already taking over the position at this point. } 13. f3 ( 13. e3 e5 14. Nb5 Qc5 $11 { a6 is a big threat and White is the one who has to be very precise. } ) 13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 { The 'h' file is now open but there is not much going on yet. } 14... Qe5 $14 { We do not necessarily need to go Kg7. One benefit is that it has not been played before. } ( 14... Kg7 15. e4 Qe5 16. Kf2 { 1/2-1/2 (45) Harikrishna,P (2743) -Kramnik,V (2779) Batumi 2018 } 16... Qf6 17. Kg1 e5 18. Nc2 Rd8 19. Qe1 Qc6 $11 { [%cal Gc8e6,Gb8d7] } ) 15. Rxh6 { The critical continuation. } ( 15. f4 Qe3 16. Nf3 gxf4 17. gxf4 Qxf4 $36 { We have a great position with e5 coming up next. } ) ( 15. Kf2 Qf6 { The queen is perfect here to prepare e5 and the move Rd8. It also defends h6. } 16. e4 e5 17. Nc2 Rd8 $36 ) 15... Qxg3+ 16. Kd2 Kg7 17. Rh3 Qc7 { The position is getting crazy and now there are many options for White. We are threatening to go for the move e5. } 18. Rh5 ( 18. Qc2 Rh8 19. Rxh8 Kxh8 20. e3 Nd7 21. Nb5 Qg3 22. c4 Kg7 $11 { The position is around equal with a lot of options for both sides. I feel better about our king compared to our opponent. } ) 18... e5 19. Rxg5+ Kf6 20. Rh5 exd4 21. cxd4 Nc6 22. Qc2 Be6 $11 { The position is dynamically balanced. All three results are certainly possible here but I would bet on a crazy repetition somewhere along the way. } ) 11... Qxa2 $1 { Once we have played the move g5, a very concrete approach is necessary. The position contains a lot of tricks for both sides. } 12. Qc2 { This line was revived by Magnus who played it against Ding. People realised that the positions are pretty complex and not easy to face over the board. } ( 12. Rc2 Qd5 { We thank White for the free pawn and will go for the move e5 next. } 13. h4 e5 14. Nf3 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 g4 16. Nxe5 Nc6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 $11 { [%csl Rd1] } ) ( 12. Bd3 { This has been played by Mamedyarov a few times. White gives up two pawns for quick development. } 12... Qxb2 13. O-O Bxc3 14. Rc2 { We force the queen back first before going Nb5. } ( 14. Nb5 { White is hell-bent on getting the knight to c7. } 14... Ba5 { We stop Nc7 and also keep the option of Qd2 open. } 15. Rb1 Qd2 16. Qxd2 Bxd2 17. Nc7 { White manages to get his knight to c7 but it is likely to be trapped soon after he takes on a8. } 17... Nc6 18. Nxa8 e5 ( 18... Rd8 $44 ) 19. Nc7 a6 { The position is very interesting as we are in no hurry to win the piece back. We can go Rd8 followed by slowly bringing the king to the center. } 20. Nxa6 { White simplifies the position but it does not lead to more than equality. } ( 20. Ra1 Rd8 21. Bc2 Kf8 $11 ) 20... bxa6 21. Rb6 Nb4 22. Rxf6 Nxd3 23. Rd1 Nc5 24. Rxd2 Ne4 25. Rdd6 Nxd6 26. Rxd6 f6 $11 ) 14... Qb4 15. Nb5 { The point is that compared to Nb5 on the previous move we do not have the Ba5 retreat, } 15... e5 16. Rxc3 Nc6 17. f4 { Definitely the way to go exploiting our weaknesses on the kingside. } ( 17. Rxc6 bxc6 18. Bxe5 Qg4 $1 { The exchange of the queens is practically forced as otherwise, the queen retreats to e6. } 19. Nc7 Qxd1 20. Rxd1 Nd7 $1 { We take the chance to get a tempo against the bishop. } 21. Bd6 Rb8 22. h3 Nb6 $11 { The position is balanced as White will win back the exchange anytime and he has the more active pieces. } ) 17... a6 { Both sides are playing on different sides of the board. White cannot afford to give up a piece yet. This has been played only once. } 18. Rb3 ( 18. Be1 Bg4 $1 19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Bxb4 Bxd1 $11 ) 18... Qe7 19. fxg5 Ng4 { We too can create threats on the kingside. } 20. Nd6 Nxe3 21. Bh7+ Kxh7 22. Rxe3 Qxg5 { We are up three pawns but White still has enough activity to compensate for it. It is dynamically balanced. } 23. Qb3 ( 23. Qe1 Qg6 24. Nc4 Bf5 25. Bxe5 Rae8 $11 ) 23... Qg6 24. Rxf7+ Rxf7 25. Nxf7 Nd4 26. Qd5 Qb1+ 27. Re1 Ne2+ 28. Kf2 Qf5+ 29. Kxe2 Be6 30. Qxb7 Bc4+ 31. Kd2 { All of this happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (31) Li, D (2579) -Xu, X (2564) Hangzhou 2022 and we can continue the game posing practical problems for White. Our king seems safer on h7. } 31... Bxf7 32. Rxe5 Rd8+ 33. Ke1 Qg6 $11 ) 12... Bxc3+ { This is the simpler option and was also played against Magnus by Wesley. } ( 12... Nd5 { This is equal but there are a lot of complications. Feel free to explore them. } 13. h4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 ( 14. hxg5 Na4+ 15. Kd1 Qxb2 16. Qxb2 Nxb2+ 17. Kc2 hxg5 18. Kxb2 Be7 $11 ) 14... Qxc2 15. Rxc2 Be7 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. f4 Nc6 18. fxg5 Bxg5 19. Rh5 f6 20. Nf3 Bxe3 21. Re2 Bc1 22. Re4 e5 23. Bc4+ Kg7 24. Reh4 Kg6 25. Rh7 e4 ( 25... Bg4 26. Bd3+ f5 27. Nxe5+ Nxe5 28. Bxe5 Kg5 29. g3 Rg8 30. Rxb7 Rae8 31. Rb5 Rg6 32. Kf2 Rb6 33. Rxb6 axb6 { 1/2-1/2 (42) Carlsen,M (2882) -Ding,L (2805) Saint Louis 2019 } ) 26. Nd2 Ne5 27. R7h6+ Kg7 28. Rh7+ Kg6 29. R4h6+ Kf5 30. Rh5+ Kg6 31. R7h6+ Kg7 32. Rh7+ Kg6 33. R7h6+ Kg7 34. Bxe5 Bxd2+ $1 ( 34... fxe5 $2 35. Rh7+ Kg6 36. Bf7+ $1 ( 36. R7h6+ Kg7 37. Rh7+ Kg6 38. R7h6+ { 1/2-1/2 (38) Sevian, S (2654) -Sunilduth Lyna, N (2611) Douglas 2019 } ) 36... Rxf7 37. R5h6+ Kg5 38. Nxe4+ $18 ) 35. Kxd2 fxe5 36. Rd6 Bf5 $11 ) 13. Qxc3 Ne4 { White faces an unpleasant choice as the queen will either get kicked around a bit or he has to allow us to give a check on a5. } 14. Qc2 { This was played by Magnus and Nepo but in rapid games. } ( 14. Qb4 a5 15. Qb5 ( 15. Qb6 Nd7 16. Qb5 Ndc5 $11 ) 15... Bd7 $1 { Development is the priority here. } 16. Qxb7 Nc6 17. Bd3 ( 17. Bc4 Qa4 18. O-O Ra7 19. Qb6 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Qb4 $11 { We get the queens off the board. } ) 17... Nxg3 18. hxg3 Rab8 $1 { We exploit the drawback of the bishop on d3. The following line is forced. } 19. Qxd7 Ne5 20. Bb1 Qxb1 21. Rxb1 Nxd7 22. Rxh6 ( 22. Ke2 Kg7 23. b3 Rfc8 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (36) Schleef, H-Faber, H freechess.de 2021 } ) 22... Nc5 $44 { We easily have enough compensation for the pawn and the endgame is pretty fighting. } ) 14... Qa5+ 15. Ke2 { Now we have a choice whether or not to trade the knight on e4. I feel it is better to preserve more pieces on the board in general with the king on e2. } 15... Nf6 $14 { We keep the pieces on the board keeping the 'h' file closed. } ( 15... Nxg3+ { happened in those two games. It is certainly possible. } 16. hxg3 Kg7 17. f4 Nc6 ( 17... Bd7 18. b4 Qxb4 19. fxg5 Rc8 $4 ( 19... Nc6 $13 ) 20. gxh6+ Kh8 21. Qxc8+ Bxc8 22. Rxc8+ Kh7 23. Nf3 $18 { 1-0 (33) Carlsen,M (2863) -So,W (2770) chess24.com INT 2020 } ) ( 17... Nd7 $5 18. b4 Qd8 $13 ) 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Kf2 Rd8 20. Rd1 Rxd1 21. Qxd1 Qf5 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (38) Nepomniachtchi,I (2784) -Leko,P (2663) chess24.com INT 2020 } ) 16. h4 ( 16. f3 { White creates a square on f2 for the king. } 16... e5 17. Nb3 Qb4 18. h4 g4 19. Qc3 Qxc3 20. Rxc3 Nc6 $11 { We have a comfortable endgame where White has to try and prove his compensation. } ) 16... g4 { Of course, we do not want to open the 'h' file unnecessarily. } 17. f3 ( 17. Qc7 b6 $15 { [%cal Gc8a6] } ) 17... e5 18. Nf5 Nc6 19. Nxh6+ Kh8 $11 { We just want to go Be6 next and bring all our pieces into the game. Our king feels safer compared to White. } *

