1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Qc2 { This can occur both via this move order and 4.Qc2. Since we do not go for the lines with d5 there we have to go for an independent option. } 5... c5 { We immediately challenge White's control over the center. } 6. dxc5 { This is the only way to pose problems for us. It is going to take us a while to complete development here. } ( 6. e3 { is too slow and we get a great position after } 6... cxd4 7. exd4 d5 $11 { There have been a few games here but I do not see the need to analyse it further. We are more comfortable as d4 is likely to be a long-term weakness. } ) ( 6. a3 { White is mixing up a few different systems which is rarely a good idea. } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 ( 7. Qxc3 { The move a3 is a complete waste here and we are able to complete our development much quicker. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 ( 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qh4 d5 $11 ) 8... d5 9. e3 e5 10. Nf3 Re8 $15 { d4 is hard to stop. } ) 7... Nc6 { We want to go d5 next. White has a few options. } 8. e4 { This is the only move which makes sense in conjunction with the move a3. White tries to bully us in the center. } ( 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. e3 b6 $5 { We want to open the 'a' file and get the light-squared bishop out to a6. The c4 pawn will fall soon. } 10. cxb6 axb6 11. Be2 Ba6 12. O-O Rfc8 $44 { We will go Ne5 next followed by winning the pawn on c4. } ) ( 8. e3 { Good luck to getting the bishop out from c1. } 8... b6 9. Bd3 Na5 10. O-O Bb7 $15 { We can go Rc8 and go after the c4 pawn next. } ) 8... d5 9. e5 Ne4 { We have seen similar lines in the 4.Qc2 variation. The inclusion of the move a3 is in our favour. } 10. Bd3 cxd4 11. Bxe4 ( 11. cxd4 $6 { allows } 11... Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 dxc4 14. Bxc4 b6 $15 ) 11... dxe4 12. Qxe4 dxc3 13. Ng5 g6 14. Be3 Qa5 $11 { White has to retreat to defend the pawn on e5. We can then go for the f6 break. } ) 6... Na6 { The bishop is doing well on b4. We want to go Nc5-e4 before White manages to castle. } 7. g3 { This is the critical continuation, developing the bishop along the long diagonal. } ( 7. c6 { It is not clear if this improves or damages our pawn structure. We can even ignore the pawn and develop our pieces. } 7... Nc5 $5 ( 7... bxc6 8. g3 e5 $11 ) 8. cxd7 Bxd7 9. Bd2 Bc6 10. Ne5 Qb6 { We have a few threats in the position. White will have to take on c6 to stop our plan with Ba4/Be4. Ne4 is another plan. } 11. Nxc6 ( 11. e3 Be4 12. Qc1 Rfd8 $19 { [%csl Re1] } ) 11... bxc6 12. g3 Nce4 $11 { We will win back one of the pawns very soon. } ) ( 7. a3 { Once again this is pretty slow and does not achieve much. } 7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 9. e3 ( 9. g3 { The direct g3 was a much better version with an extra tempo. } 9... b6 { We get the chance to neutralise the bishop easily. } 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O Rc8 { Our next move is going to be d5 and the position is even. } ) ( 9. b4 $6 { This creates a weakness for us to attack on the queenside. } 9... Nce4 10. Qd4 ( 10. Qb2 a5 $15 ) 10... d6 11. Ng5 ( 11. Bg5 Nxg5 12. Nxg5 { Happened in the game 0-1 (32) Fodor, T (2500) -Nakamura, H (2787) Caleta 2016 and Black had a huge edge after } 12... e5 $17 ) 11... e5 12. Qb2 a5 $15 { White is lagging in development and his queenside is coming under pressure too. } ) 9... a5 $5 { We gain space on the queenside and create a threat of a4 fixing the weakness on b3. } 10. b3 { This does not secure the queenside as we will go a4 and plant our knight on b3 at the right moment. } ( 10. b4 { We now get a nice sequence of moves. } 10... Nce4 11. Qb2 Ng4 $1 { suddenly there is no way to defend the pawn on f2! } 12. Be2 ( 12. h3 Ngxf2 $19 { 0-1 (30) Hagen,A (2084) -Koskela,N (2191) Oslo 2010 } ) 12... Ngxf2 13. O-O Ng4 14. Qd4 d5 $11 { We have an extra pawn and White has to prove his compensation still. } ) 10... d6 11. Be2 Nfe4 12. Qb2 a4 13. b4 Nb3 14. Rb1 e5 $15 { The knights are doing an amazing job. We can go Be6 and f5 followed by an eventual f4. } ) ( 7. Bd2 { White decides to get his bishop to c3. } 7... Nxc5 8. e3 ( 8. a3 { The usual non-developing move wasting precious time. } 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nce4 { We will win the bishop one way or the other. } 10. e3 ( 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. e4 d6 12. Bd3 e5 13. O-O Be6 $11 { I prefer Black with the better bishop. } ) 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 b6 12. Be2 Ba6 { We are going after the c4 pawn. } 13. Qb3 ( 13. O-O Rc8 $15 { [%cal Gd7d5] } ) 13... Rc8 14. Qa4 Bb7 15. O-O { Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (65) Nakamura,H (2764) -Caruana, F (2844) Tashkent 2014. I like Black's position more after } 15... Bc6 16. Qb3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Rc5 18. Qd3 Qc7 19. b3 a5 $11 ) 8... b6 { Once we establish our bishop on the long diagonal it is going to be hard for White to create anything. We will have full control over e4. } 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Nce4 { We can trade a few pieces and go for the d5 break. } 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 d5 $11 { We have managed to equalise pretty easily. } ) 7... Nxc5 8. Bg2 Nce4 { We need to damage our opponent's pawn structure to compensate for his lead in development. } ( 8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nb5 Be4 11. Qd1 Nb7 12. a3 Be7 13. Bf4 { is a bit unpleasant for black 1/2-1/2 (78) Nakamura, H (2779) -Topalov,V (2760) Saint Louis 2016 } ) 9. O-O { Now there are two different approaches to go for. Both of them are similar- we damage White's pawn structure but we are lagging in development. } ( 9. Bd2 { White gives up the bishop pair to preserve his pawn structure. } 9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 Rb8 { We need to develop our light-squared bishop either on b7 or a6. } 11. O-O b6 12. Rfd1 ( 12. e4 { This restricts the bishop on g2 and creates a hole on d4. } 12... d6 13. Rfd1 Bb7 14. a3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qc7 $11 { We get a great version of the Sicilian with the e4 pawn under a lot of pressure. In such positions the exchange of minor pieces favours us. } ) 12... a5 { This is an unusual move as we voluntarily weaken the b5 square. However, we need to stop his plan of a3,b4. White cannot exploit the weakness on b5 easily. } 13. Nde4 ( 13. a3 Be7 14. Qd3 Ba6 15. b4 Qc7 $11 ) 13... Ba6 { We would like to provoke the move b3 as it creates some weaknesses. } 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Ne4 Qd8 16. a3 Be7 17. b3 Qc7 $11 { I prefer Black with the bishop iar. We are threatening to go d5 now. } ) 9... Bxc3 { This is a responsible decision giving up the bishop pair. But we believe in our knight on e4 and want to finish development quickly. } ( 9... Nxc3 { This was my plan earlier but the resulting positions are passive with no chances to play for a win. I will give my analysis without comments. } 10. bxc3 Be7 11. e4 $1 ( 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Qd3 d6 ( 12... Rd8 $1 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] } ) 13. Rb1 Rb8 14. Be3 b6 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Nb5 Bxb5 17. cxb5 Rbc8 18. Bc6 Ng4 19. Bf4 Ne5 20. Bxe5 dxe5 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (29) Mamedyarov, S (2772) -Aronian, L (2772) Bucharest 2019 } ) 11... d6 12. e5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 Qc7 14. Qe2 ( 14. Re1 Bd6 15. Qe2 ( 15. Bf4 Nh5 16. Rad1 Nxf4 17. gxf4 a5 $17 ) 15... Nd7 16. Bf4 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 ) 14... Nd7 $1 ( 14... Bd6 15. Bf4 $1 Ne8 { [%cal Gf7f6] } ( 15... Nd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Bxb7 Rab8 19. Rab1 Qc7 20. Be4 Bc6 21. Rxb8 Rxb8 22. Rd1 h6 { with almost a draw but black is playing only for two results } ) 16. c5 $1 Qxc5 17. c4 f6 ( 17... Qc7 18. Rfd1 f6 19. Nd3 Bxf4 20. Nxf4 e5 21. Nd5 Qc5 22. Rab1 Nc7 23. Qd3 Rb8 24. Nxc7 Qxc7 25. Bd5+ Kh8 26. Qa3 Rd8 27. Qxa7 Bf5 28. Qb6 Qxb6 29. Rxb6 Be4 { again most probably a draw but black has to be precise } ) ( 17... Rb8 18. Rfe1 f6 19. Nd3 Qxc4 20. Rac1 Qa6 21. Rxc8 Bxf4 22. Rc3 Bd6 23. Qxe6+ Kh8 24. Rec1 $14 ) 18. Nd3 Qc7 19. Bd2 Qf7 20. c5 Bc7 21. Bb4 $14 { [%csl Gb4,Gg2] } ) 15. Bf4 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bd6 17. Rfe1 { tr } 17... Bxe5 ( 17... Rb8 18. Rad1 Bxe5 19. Qxe5 Qxe5 20. Rxe5 b6 21. c5 Ba6 ( 21... f6 22. cxb6 axb6 23. Re2 Kf7 { 1-0 (55) Navara,D (2730) -Caruana,F (2787) Wijk aan Zee 2016 } ) 22. c6 ( 22. h4 Rfd8 23. Rb1 Bc4 24. cxb6 Rxb6 25. Rb4 Bxa2 26. Ra5 Bd5 27. Bxd5 exd5 { 1/2-1/2 (28) Topalov,V (2740) -Dominguez Perez,L (2739) Saint Louis 2019 } ) 22... Rbc8 23. Bf3 ( 23. Rd7 Rfd8 24. Re4 Rxd7 25. cxd7 Rd8 26. Ra4 Bb5 27. Rxa7 Kf8 28. Bf1 Bxd7 { 1/2-1/2 (43) Nakamura,H (2781) -Caruana,F (2799) London 2017 } ) 23... Rc7 24. Rd4 Re8 25. a4 Kf8 26. Re1 Bc8 27. a5 bxa5 28. Re5 Ke7 29. Rxa5 Rd8 30. Rb4 a6 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (36) Xiong,J (2712) -Caruana,F (2822) Wijk aan Zee 2020 } ) 18. Qxe5 Qxc4 19. Red1 ( 19. Qa5 Bd7 20. Bxb7 Rab8 21. Rab1 h6 22. Qxa7 Qc7 23. Qa6 Qxc3 24. Rec1 Qd2 25. Rd1 Qc2 26. Qd6 Ba4 27. Be4 Qc8 28. Rbc1 Qd8 29. Qxd8 Rfxd8 { 1/2-1/2 (38) Balta, M (2315) -Rolle, H (2273) ICCF email 2018 } ) ( 19. Rad1 Qxa2 20. Qc7 e5 $11 ) ( 19. a3 Bd7 20. Bxb7 Rad8 21. Re4 Qb5 22. Qxb5 Bxb5 23. c4 f5 24. Rxe6 Bxc4 $11 ) 19... a5 20. a4 ( 20. Bf1 Qa4 $11 ) ( 20. a3 h6 21. Rab1 f6 22. Qd6 Re8 23. Bf1 ( 23. Bxb7 Bxb7 24. Rxb7 Kh8 $11 ) 23... Qc6 24. Bb5 Qxd6 25. Rxd6 Rf8 $11 ) 20... h6 ( 20... f6 21. Qd6 Re8 22. Bf1 Qc6 23. Bb5 Qxd6 24. Rxd6 Rf8 25. Rad1 e5 26. Bc4+ Kh8 27. Bd5 Ra7 $11 ) 21. Bf1 ( 21. h4 f6 22. Qd6 Qxc3 23. Rab1 Qe5 24. Qxe5 fxe5 $11 ) ( 21. Ra3 f6 22. Qb5 Qxb5 23. axb5 Rf7 24. Rd8+ Rf8 25. Rd4 Rf7 ) 21... Qc6 22. Rd6 Qc7 23. Rxe6 Qxe5 24. Rxe5 Be6 $11 ) 10. bxc3 d5 { This has been played only a few times but it makes sense as it opens up the diagonal for our bishop. It eliminates one of White's weak pawns though. } ( 10... Qc7 { is the main move. } ) 11. cxd5 { White is going to try and get rid of his weak pawns. It is a win-win for both sides since we are also able to finish our development. } ( 11. Bf4 Re8 { This is a useful flexible move asking White what he intends to do. } 12. Rfd1 Ng4 $1 { An idea we are already familiar with. } 13. Rd4 Qa5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. c4 Ngxf2 $11 { The position remains very complex but it is dynamically balanced. } ) ( 11. Nd4 Re8 { This seems to be the standard move to go for in these positions as White is bound to take on d5 at some point. } 12. cxd5 exd5 13. c4 dxc4 14. Qxc4 h5 $11 { We can go h4-h3 next. The knight is very well placed on e4. } ) ( 11. Ng5 { A very aggressive move but not sure what it achieves after } 11... Nd6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Ba3 ( 13. Bf4 h6 14. Nf3 { 0-1 (52) Milikow,Y (2416) -Keymer,V (2696) Chess.com INT 2022 } 14... Re8 $11 { We will go b6 and Ba6 next. } ) ( 13. Rd1 h6 14. Nf3 b6 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. c4 Be6 $11 { These positions can go wrong for White pretty quickly in the endgame as we have a majority on the queenside. } ) 13... Re8 14. Rfd1 Bf5 15. Qb2 h6 16. Bxd5 ( 16. Nf3 Nc4 $17 ) 16... Nxd5 17. Rxd5 hxg5 18. Bxd6 Be4 $11 { We have good chances to create an attack on the kingside. As we know in opposite colour bishop middlegames, king safety is more important compared to material. } ) ( 11. Nd2 { White decided to exchange our active knight but more trades generally favour us. White's pawns will come under fire in major piece endgames. } 11... Nxd2 12. Bxd2 dxc4 13. Bg5 e5 14. Rfd1 Qc7 $11 { We will continue with Be6 followed by bringing the rooks to the 'd' file. } ) 11... exd5 12. c4 ( 12. Be3 { The bishop has a nice square on d4 but the pawn on c3 will remain a weakness. } 12... Re8 13. Bd4 Bf5 14. Qb2 b6 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. Nd3 Nd7 $1 { We are bringing the knight to e6 to dislodge the bishop on d4. } 17. a4 Nf8 18. Nf4 Ne6 $11 ) 12... Bf5 { We have managed to complete our development with a tempo. } 13. Qb3 ( 13. Nh4 Be6 { The knight is now misplaced in the corner. } 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Bb2 Rfc8 16. Qb1 Qc4 17. Bxf6 { A necessity as our pieces were just too active. } 17... Nxf6 18. Qxb7 Qxe2 $11 { The position has simplified and is just equal. } ) 13... dxc4 { This is simpler and more forcing. We get to kick the queen around for a bit. } ( 13... Be6 14. cxd5 ( 14. Rd1 dxc4 15. Qc2 Qa5 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. Qxc4 Rac8 18. Qd3 Rc3 19. Qb1 Ba4 20. Rf1 Qd5 21. Be3 Rfc8 $11 ) 14... Bxd5 15. Qd3 Re8 16. Be3 Qa5 $11 ) 14. Qxc4 Rc8 15. Qb5 ( 15. Qb3 Nc3 $15 ) 15... Nd6 { We shift our pieces around a bit. The bishop would be ideal on e4. The queen lacks a good square on the board. } 16. Qb3 Bc2 17. Qb2 Be4 18. Rd1 Nd5 { I like our pieces in the middle of the board. White will have to trade the light-squared bishops at some point and we do have a queenside majority in the endgames. } 19. Ng5 Nc4 20. Qxb7 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nde3+ 22. Bxe3 Nxe3+ 23. fxe3 Qxg5 $11 *
