1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 { This is called the Leningrad system and it is one of the more aggressive options for White. However, in modern times it has gone out of practice as engines like the resulting positions for Black. } 4... c5 { We have already seen that this is particularly effective against the Bg5 systems. } 5. d5 ( 5. e3 $2 { is a huge mistake due to } 5... Qa5 $1 6. Ne2 Ne4 7. Qd3 cxd4 8. exd4 Nxf2 9. Kxf2 Qxg5 $17 ) ( 5. dxc5 { leads to a very comfortable position after } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qd4 e5 9. Qe3 Na6 $15 { We have a much better pawn structure and the knight would be very well placed on c5. } ) ( 5. Nf3 O-O { transposes to another file. } ) 5... d6 6. e3 { White decides to build his center a bit more slowly. We have two options- to go for some forcing lines or to play a more strategic game. } ( 6. e4 { is too soon } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15 ) ( 6. Nf3 exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7 8. Nd2 { White is trying to play in Benoni style but we have our bishop out on b4 which makes it easier to target White's center. } 8... O-O 9. e4 Qe8 10. Qf3 ( 10. f3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxd5 $15 ) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxd5 { We win a pawn and even though White has some compensation it is not enough for equality. } ) ( 6. f3 h6 7. Bh4 ( 7. Bd2 O-O 8. e4 exd5 9. cxd5 Nh5 $1 { This is a common idea in these lines with f3. It creates a threat of Qh4 and also prepares the f5 break. } 10. Qe2 f5 $15 ) 7... O-O 8. e4 Re8 { I love such positions where we have finished development and just play natural moves targeting our opponent's king in the center. } 9. dxe6 { This is practically forced. } ( 9. Bd3 $4 exd5 10. cxd5 Nxe4 $19 ) ( 9. Qc2 exd5 10. cxd5 a6 $17 { It is going to be very hard to develop the kingside pieces for White. The bishop can only go to e2 as otherwise it will be harassed with b5, c4. } ) 9... Bxe6 10. Bd3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 $15 { We have the better minor piece, pawn structure and development, What more do we need? } ) 6... Bxc3+ { We take on c3 immediately after White goes e3 preparing the move Nge2. } ( 6... h6 { gives an extra option in } 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Ne2 $11 ) ( 6... exd5 { This equalises concretely and you can check it out in more detail. However, we will face these lines once in 50 games and it makes sense to prepare something which is not forcing and is more strategic. } 7. cxd5 Nbd7 8. Bd3 ( 8. Bb5 h6 9. Bh4 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5 ( 10... O-O $5 11. Ne2 Nb6 12. O-O Nbxd5 13. Bd3 Bg4 $1 14. Rc1 Re8 15. h3 Bd7 16. c4 Nb6 17. Nc3 Bc6 $11 ) 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Ne2 O-O 13. O-O ( 13. Be7 Re8 14. Bxd6 Nf6 15. O-O Bg4 16. Bg3 Nxd5 $15 ) 13... Re8 $15 ) 8... Qa5 9. Ne2 Nxd5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 c4 $1 12. Bc2 ( 12. Be4 N5f6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Bf3 Qc5 $15 ) 12... O-O 13. Bh4 ( 13. Qd4 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxg5 15. Qxc4 Nf6 16. Ne4 Qe5 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 ) ( 13. Ng3 Nxc3 14. Qh5 f5 15. Be7 Rf7 16. Bxd6 ( 16. Nxf5 Ne5 17. Bxd6 Bxf5 18. Bxf5 Nf3+ 19. Qxf3 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Ne2+ 21. Kh1 Rxf5 $17 ) 16... Qb6 17. Ba3 Ne5 18. Rfc1 g6 19. Qh4 Bd7 20. Bxf5 Bxf5 21. Rxc3 Bd3 $17 ) ( 13. a4 Re8 ( 13... Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxc3 15. Be7 Re8 16. Bxd6 Qf6 17. a5 ( 17. f4 Re6 ) 17... Ne5 ( 17... h6 18. f4 Re6 19. Bb4 ) 18. Qd5 Bf5 19. e4 Rad8 20. Bxe5 Rxe5 21. Qxb7 ) ( 13... h6 14. Bh4 Nxc3 15. Nxc3 Qxc3 16. Rc1 Qe5 17. Bg3 Qe6 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Bxd6 Re8 20. Bb1 b6 21. Ba2 ) 14. Qd2 Nxc3 15. Nxc3 Qxg5 16. Ne4 Qe7 17. Nxd6 Rd8 18. Nf5 Qf6 19. Rfd1 b6 20. Qd6 Qxd6 21. Rxd6 Kf8 ( 21... Re8 22. Rd4 Nc5 23. Rxc4 g6 24. Nd4 Bd7 25. a5 ) 22. Rad1 Rb8 23. Nd4 ) 13... Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxc3 15. Rc1 Qe5 ( 15... Qa3 $5 16. Be7 Re8 17. Bxd6 Qa6 ) 16. Bg3 Qe6 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 ( 17... Nf6 18. Qb4 a5 19. Qb1 Qc6 20. Rfd1 b5 21. Rd6 Qc5 22. Rd4 Be6 23. Bd6 Qc6 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 $44 ) 18. Bxd6 Re8 ( 18... Rd8 $11 ) 19. Rfd1 Nb6 ( 19... Nf6 20. Ba4 Rd8 21. Bb5 Ne4 ( 21... Be6 22. Bxc4 Rac8 23. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 ) 22. Be7 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Be6 24. Rd4 Nf6 25. Bxc4 Rc8 26. Bf1 Nd5 { [%csl Ga7,Gb7] } ) 20. a4 Bd7 21. a5 Na4 22. Bb4 Bb5 23. Rd5 a6 $11 ) 7. bxc3 h6 8. Bh4 e5 { We gave up our bishop damaging the opponent's pawn structure and now we close down the center. This should suit our knights more than White's bishops. Both sides have different ways of playing here. Our king can go to the kingside or we have this idea to go Kd7-c7 where it is pretty safe. } 9. Qc2 { White stops us from going Bf5 but we will anyway go e4 first followed by Bf5. } ( 9. Nf3 { White should not allow us to get our bishop to f5 so easily. } 9... g5 10. Bg3 Bf5 $1 { This is the perfect diagonal for the bishop. It keeps an eye on the e4 square too. } 11. Nd2 Qe7 12. f3 { White has to try and get in the move e4. } 12... e4 $1 { Of course we instantly stop it. } 13. Be2 exf3 14. Bxf3 Bd3 ( 14... h5 $5 15. e4 h4 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. O-O Nbd7 18. exf5 O-O-O $15 ) 15. Be2 Bg6 $15 { We have a nice outpost on e5 and White has a clear weakness on the semi-open 'e' file. } ) ( 9. Bd3 { White attempts to stop Bf5 but this allows us to go e4 with a tempo. The move e4 is usually in our plans anyway. } 9... g5 10. Bg3 e4 11. Bc2 Qe7 12. h4 Rg8 { Castling kingside was never in the picture and we do not mind playing Rg8. h4 also weakens White's kingside. } 13. Ne2 Nbd7 14. Qb1 Kf8 $1 { This is a surprise but our king is pretty safe on g7 and it can be used to fight for the 'h' file in the future. } 15. Kd2 Nb6 16. Qb3 Bf5 $15 { Our next plan would be to go Rb8, Nd7-e5. } ) ( 9. f3 g5 $1 10. Bg3 ( 10. Bf2 { What is the drawback here? } 10... e4 $1 { We need to stop White from going e4 and f4 is not as good as it was with the bishop g3. } 11. f4 ( 11. Ne2 Nbd7 12. Ng3 exf3 13. gxf3 Ne5 14. Be2 Bh3 $17 { We will castle long next. } ) 11... Nbd7 { We are not in a hurry. We can bring the knight to the kingside via f8. } 12. Nh3 ( 12. Ne2 Ng4 13. Bg1 f5 $17 ) 12... g4 13. Ng1 Nf8 14. Bh4 Ng6 $17 ) 10... Kd7 $1 { This is a perfect position to showcase our idea of bringing the king to the queenside. We want to then start our play on the kingside with h5. } ( 10... e4 11. f4 $1 Nbd7 12. Nh3 $11 ) 11. e4 ( 11. Bd3 Kc7 12. Ne2 Qe7 13. a4 a5 14. Rb1 Rg8 $15 { h5 is coming up next. } ) 11... Kc7 12. Ne2 Nh5 { Now we will go for the move f5 next. It is a dream version of KID for us as we have managed to rid of our worst piece and get a super safe square for our king. } 13. Bf2 Qf8 $15 { [%cal Gf7f5] } ) 9... g5 10. Bg3 Qe7 { We are preparing e4. We are not too bothered about White going for e4 as we can then play f5 soon. } ( 10... e4 { is a bit premature. } 11. h4 Rg8 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. f4 $11 ) 11. Nf3 e4 $5 { I like to gain space in the center and get my bishop to f5. This leads to more confrontations in the center as White is bound to go f3 at some point. } ( 11... Kd8 { [%csl Gc7] This is another way of playing without going for the move e4. You can choose based on your preference. } 12. Nd2 Kc7 13. Bd3 Nbd7 14. a4 a5 15. Bf5 ( 15. Nb1 Nb6 16. Na3 Bd7 $15 ) 15... Nh5 16. O-O Ndf6 17. Bxc8 Raxc8 18. f3 Nd7 $11 { [%cal Gh5g7,Gf7f5] } ) 12. Nd2 Bf5 13. Be2 { This is probably the best followed by castling long. } ( 13. Rb1 O-O { With White's pieces focussing on the queenside I feel safe getting our king to g8. We will bring our knight to e5 and go f5-f4 in the future. } 14. Be2 Bg6 15. O-O ( 15. h4 b6 16. Kd1 Nbd7 $17 ) 15... b6 { We prepare to bring our knight into the game. } 16. a4 Nbd7 17. a5 Ne8 $15 { f5-f4 is a big threat now and the knight will go to g7-h5/f5. White has to be very careful to survive. } ) 13... Nbd7 14. h4 Bh7 { We will wait for White to decide with his king before committing to either side of the board. The king is likely to head to the kingside though. } 15. O-O-O Kf8 { I like the king on g7 keeping an eye on h8. The rook is already playing well on h8. } 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Rh2 Kg7 18. Rdh1 Ne5 19. Qd1 Bg6 $36 { We can go Nd3 at any moment. a6, b5 is a potential idea to open up the queenside. } *

