1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 { This has completely gone out of practice and it makes sense as we have a clear way to punish White for bringing his queen out too early. } ( 4. Bd2 { We have already seen this in the previous database. } ) 4... c5 $1 { This is very effective here with the queen on b3. Ne4 is in the air and the queen is completely misplaced. } 5. dxc5 ( 5. Nf3 Nc6 { We are trying to force him to release the tension. } 6. e3 ( 6. d5 Na5 { [%csl Rc4] } ) 6... cxd4 7. exd4 ( 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Nxc6 dxc6 { [%cal Ge6e5] } 9. Be2 e5 $11 { We have managed to open the diagonal for the bishop and have a very pleasant position. White cannot do the same as e4 becomes a big weakness. } ) 7... d5 { We will take on c4 as soon as White develops his light-squared bishop. The d4 pawn will then come under fire. } 8. Bg5 { This is the most played move but it does not fit in with the queen on b3. } ( 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. Bc4 Qd6 10. O-O O-O { We have a huge threat of Na5 winning a piece. Also, the d4 pawn is hanging. } 11. Be2 ( 11. Rd1 $4 Na5 $19 ) 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Be3 Qa5 $11 { Engines claim that White has enough compensation and while I do agree it is easier to play as Black. We can try to get e5 and Be6 next. } ) 8... O-O 9. Be2 ( 9. cxd5 exd5 $15 { [%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e1] } ) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 dxc4 { This is almost automatic once the bishop moves away from f1. } 11. Bxc4 h6 12. Bh4 Nd5 $1 { A good simplification giving us a nice endgame edge. } 13. Bxd8 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Rxd8 $15 { [%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Gc8d7,Gc6e7,Ga8c8] } ) 5... Nc6 { [%cal Gf6e4,Gc6d4,Gd8a5] We are ready to jump in with Ne4. Qa5 and Nd4 are also in the air. } 6. Nf3 ( 6. Bg5 { Again, this does not achieve anything here. } 6... h6 7. Bxf6 ( 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 $15 ) 7... Qxf6 8. Nf3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 b6 $1 { Our main idea is to go after the pawn on c4 next. We clear the route for the bishop to a6. } 11. cxb6 axb6 $15 ) 6... Ne4 7. Bd2 Nxd2 { This was a pretty important bishop creating some idea for White. } 8. Nxd2 Bxc5 9. g3 ( 9. e3 { is timid and allows us to go } 9... O-O 10. Be2 b6 $11 ) ( 9. Nde4 Be7 $15 ) 9... Qb6 $1 { We get the queens off the board. } 10. Qxb6 Bxb6 11. Bg2 Ke7 $11 { Our king is well placed in the endgame and we have the bishop pair. White has a very active bishop and somewhat better-placed pieces. The position is balanced. It happened in the game 0-1 (71) Aravindh, C (2625) -Shyam, N (2489) Waskaduwa 2022. } *
