 {[#]} {How to continue here?} 9... Qa5 $1 {I like to deviate early from the
well-trodden path. We want to discoordinate White's pieces and tie them down
to the c3 pawn.} (9... b6 {This was the main line of my analysis and what Nepo
played. You can check this more deeply on your own.} 10. e4 Ba6 11. Bg5 h6 12.
h4 $1 {White keeps the tension on the kingside.} hxg5 {The most direct way.}
13. hxg5 g6 14. gxf6 Qxf6 15. e5 (15. Qg4 {This is what I had prepared for
White before that game.} cxd4 16. Nh5 Qe5 17. f4 Qxe4+ 18. Be2 Qb1+ 19. Bd1
Qe4+ $11) 15... dxe5 16. d5 $5 {This is where Ding deviates from the top line
of the computer.} Ne7 17. d6 Nf5 18. Ne4 Qd8 19. Qd3 Kg7 20. g4 Bb7 21. Rh3 Nh4
22. g5 {All this happened in 1/2-1/2 (45) Ding, L (2788) -Nepomniachtchi, I 
(2795) Astana 2023. Black would have been fine after} Rh8 $1 23. f4 exf4 24.
Nf6 e5 25. Rah2 Nf3+ 26. Qxf3 Bxf3 27. Rh7+ Rxh7 28. Rxh7+ Kf8 29. Rh8+ Kg7 $11
) 10. Rd2 (10. Bd2 {This beats the purpose of going Ra2 and we can just go
back.} Qc7 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6]}) 10... d5 {With a lead in development we
are happy to open up the center.} 11. cxd5 (11. Bb2 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 {We can
go for the move e5 next. The bishop on b2 is completely shut down.} 13. Qc2 f5
$11) 11... exd5 {We want to go c4 now and keep the center closed. We are
playing against the bishop on c1.} 12. Be2 c4 13. Qc2 Re8 14. O-O Bd7 $11 {
We can go Ne7 followed by Ba4. On the kingside we can try to go h5-h4. The
position is balanced.} *

