 {[#]} {How to continue here?} 10... Nc6 $5 {We are preparing to go Na5 next.
White has to act quickly.} (10... Nbd7 {This is a simpler and maybe even
better option objectively. It does not lead to forcing play here.} 11. Nf4 Bf5
12. h3 c6 $11 {We can go h6 next and we have a pleasant middlegame. I like our
chances more.}) 11. d5 $1 {White has to enter these complications.} (11. O-O {
is too slow and allows us to execute our plan.} Na5 12. d5 Bd7 13. Ng3 b6 $17 {
[%csl Rc3,Rc4]}) 11... Ne5 12. dxe6 Nd3+ 13. Kf1 Ng4 (13... Ng4 {This must
look very scary to play for White and he has to find some only moves.} 14. Nf4
Ngxf2 15. e7 $1 {This is very important here not allowing us to open the 'f'
file.} Qxe7 16. Qd2 {Again the only move. This is a weird square for the queen
but necessary as exd3 should not come with a tempo.} (16. Qe2 $4 Nxh1 17. Nxd3
exd3 18. Qxd3 Qf6+ $19) 16... Nxh1 17. Nxd3 exd3 18. Kg1 {We have quite a few
options here to continue our initiative.} Qf6 (18... Rae8 {is a promising
option.} 19. Kxh1 f5 20. Qxd3 f4 21. c5+ d5 22. Bxd5+ Kh8 23. e4 c6 24. Bb3
Qxe4 25. Qxe4 Rxe4 26. Kg1 $11) 19. Bb2 Rae8 20. Kxh1 Re4 {This is a very
messy position but dynamically balanced. We will look to create something
quickly on the kingside.} 21. Kg1 Qe5 22. Re1 Re8 23. Bc1 Rh4 24. g3 Re6 $1 {
We bring all our pieces into the game. There are too many options here to
analyse very deeply. I think this is already far from the realms of
possibility in a practical game.} 25. Qxd3 Rh3 26. Re2 Rg6 27. Rg2 (27. Qd2
Rgxg3+ 28. hxg3 Qxg3+ 29. Rg2 Qh4 30. Kf1 Rh1+ 31. Rg1 Rh2 32. Rg2 $11) 27...
Rxh2 28. Kxh2 Qh5+ 29. Kg1 Rh6 30. Kf2 Rf6+ $11) *


