 {[#]} {How to continue here?} 11... Qc7 $1 {As I mentioned earlier we keep
both options open for as long as possible. The other point is to stop his idea
of Bg5 especially when we castle kingside.} 12. Ng3 (12. f4 O-O-O $1 {the
point of blacks play...he is very flexible with the king} 13. f5 e5 14. d5 Bxc4
15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Bg5 Nxe4 17. Bxd8 Rxd8 $15) 12... O-O {[%csl Rc4] We have
already seen that with the knight on g3, we can commit to castling kingside.}
13. f4 {This is in the spirit of the position- to go for an all-out attack
against our king.} (13. Rf2 {White is trying to preserve the bishops on the
board but it wastes a lot of time.} Bxc4 14. Bc2 Rac8 $15) 13... Bxc4 14. f5
cxd4 15. cxd4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qc4 (16... Qc4 {We are going to try our best to
get the queens off the board.} 17. Qd1 h6 {We first stop ideas of Bg5. Let us
see what White is going to try on the kingside.} (17... Qb3 18. Qe1 {[%cal
Ge3g5]}) 18. Kh1 (18. Rc1 Qb3 $11) 18... Rac8 (18... Qb3 19. Qe2 e5 $11) 19.
Nh5 Nxh5 20. Qxh5 exf5 21. exf5 Rfe8 22. Bxh6 {This is the only way to keep
the balance for White.} Qxd4 23. Rad1 Qe5 24. Rf3 Qe1+ 25. Rf1 Qe5 {A very
professional repetition of moves :)}) *


