 {[#]} {How to continue here?} 10... Rb8 {We get the rook out of the dangerous
h1-a8 diagonal and prepare the move b5.} 11. e4 (11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 c6 $11 {
We keep the d5 square secure. The pin is not a big deal now since we have the
move Nb4.}) 11... Ncb4 (11... Ndb4 {is also possible but I want to keep the
option to take on c3.}) 12. Qd2 (12. Qe2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5]
Black is doing very well with c5 to follow.}) (12. Qb1 {White anticipates the
opening of the 'b' file but even in the best-case scenario, White wins back
the pawn and nothing else.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 14. Qb5 Nxc1 {We eliminate a key
minor piece.} 15. Raxc1 Bd7 16. Qxc4 c5 {All our plans have been executed well.
} 17. Ne5 (17. dxc5 Qc7 $15) 17... b5 18. Qe2 Be8 $11 {We can go c4 and start
pushing our pawns on the queenside.}) 12... Nxc3 {Exchanging of pieces favour
us here as we have less space.} 13. Qxc3 b5 14. b3 Bb7 $1 {We win a tempo
against the e4 pawn and force White to make some concession.} (14... cxb3 15.
Qxb3 {White has very good compensation here as we are forced to retreat with
our knight.}) 15. Ne1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ga2a3] White covers the d3 square and
is threatening to go a3 next.} (15. a3 {allows the simple} Nd3 16. bxc4 Nxc1 {
We win the bishop pair and also the pawn on e4. Now White is fighting for
equality.} 17. Rdxc1 Bxe4 18. Ne5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Rb6 20. cxb5 Rxb5 $11 {White
will probably win back the pawn but we have nothing to worry about.}) 15...
cxb3 16. axb3 (16. Qxb3 a5 {Our pawns are quite dangerous on the queenside.}
17. Bf4 Qd7 18. Rab1 a4 19. Qc3 {White is trying to tempt us into taking the
pawn on a2 as he can then trap the knight.} Nxa2 $1 {We do it anyway as our
pawns are more than enough compensation for the piece.} 20. Qd2 b4 21. Qxa2 b3
22. Qe2 Bc6 $15 {White has to play very precisely to survive here.}) 16... Ra8
17. Bb2 {The threat here is to go d5 and we have to act prophylactically.} Bd6
$11 {We are ready to meet d5 with e5 and I do not see a clear way for White to
equalise.} *

